# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chaos-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] The name "bifurcation" was first introduced by Henri Poincaré in 1885 in the first paper in mathematics showing such a behavior.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] A local bifurcation occurs when a parameter change causes the stability of an equilibrium (or fixed point) to change.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] In continuous systems, this corresponds to the real part of an eigenvalue of an equilibrium passing through zero.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] In discrete systems (described by maps), this corresponds to a fixed point having a Floquet multiplier with modulus equal to one.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] In both cases, the equilibrium is *non-hyperbolic* at the bifurcation point.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] The topological changes in the phase portrait of the system can be confined to arbitrarily small neighbourhoods of the bifurcating fixed points by moving the bifurcation parameter close to the bifurcation point (hence "local").
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] If the eigenvalue is equal to zero, the bifurcation is a steady-state bifurcation, but if the eigenvalue is non-zero but purely imaginary, this is a Hopf bifurcation.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] For discrete dynamical systems, consider the system $x_{n+1}=f(x_{n},\lambda ).$ Then a local bifurcation occurs at $(x_{0},\lambda _{0})$ if the matrix ${\textrm {d}}f_{x_{0},\lambda _{0}}$ has an eigenvalue with modulus equal to one.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] If the eigenvalue is equal to one, the bifurcation is either a saddle-node (often called fold bifurcation in maps), transcritical or pitchfork bifurcation.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] If the eigenvalue is equal to −1, it is a period-doubling (or flip) bifurcation, and otherwise, it is a Hopf bifurcation.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] Global bifurcations occur when "larger" invariant sets, such as periodic orbits, collide with equilibria.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] This causes changes in the topology of the trajectories in the phase space which cannot be confined to a small neighbourhood, as is the case with local bifurcations.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] In fact, the changes in topology extend out to an arbitrarily large distance (hence "global").
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] Global bifurcations can also involve more complicated sets such as chaotic attractors (e.g. crises).
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] The codimension of a bifurcation is the number of parameters which must be varied for the bifurcation to occur.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] This corresponds to the codimension of the parameter set for which the bifurcation occurs within the full space of parameters.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] Saddle-node bifurcations and Hopf bifurcations are the only generic local bifurcations which are really codimension-one (the others all having higher codimension).
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] However, transcritical and pitchfork bifurcations are also often thought of as codimension-one, because the normal forms can be written with only one parameter.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] An example of a well-studied codimension-two bifurcation is the Bogdanov–Takens bifurcation.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] Bifurcation theory has been applied to connect quantum systems to the dynamics of their classical analogues in atomic systems, molecular systems, and resonant tunneling diodes.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] Bifurcation theory has also been applied to the study of laser dynamics and a number of theoretical examples which are difficult to access experimentally such as the kicked top and coupled quantum wells.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] The dominant reason for the link between quantum systems and bifurcations in the classical equations of motion is that at bifurcations, the signature of classical orbits becomes large, as Martin Gutzwiller points out in his classic work on quantum chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/bifurcation-theory] Many kinds of bifurcations have been studied with regard to links between classical and quantum dynamics including saddle node bifurcations, Hopf bifurcations, umbilic bifurcations, period doubling bifurcations, reconnection bifurcations, tangent bifurcations, and cusp bifurcations.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] In chaos theory, the **butterfly effect** is the sensitive dependence on initial conditions in which a small change in one state of a deterministic nonlinear system can result in large differences in a later state.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The term is closely associated with the work of the mathematician and meteorologist Edward Norton Lorenz.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] He noted that the butterfly effect is derived from the example of the details of a tornado (the exact time of formation, the exact path taken) being influenced by minor perturbations such as a distant butterfly flapping its wings several weeks earlier.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Lorenz originally used a seagull causing a storm but was persuaded to make it more poetic with the use of a butterfly and tornado by 1972.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] He discovered the effect when he observed runs of his weather model with initial condition data that were rounded in a seemingly inconsequential manner.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] He noted that the weather model would fail to reproduce the results of runs with the unrounded initial condition data.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] A very small change in initial conditions had created a significantly different outcome.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The idea that small causes may have large effects in weather was earlier acknowledged by the French mathematician and physicist Henri Poincaré.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The American mathematician and philosopher Norbert Wiener also contributed to this theory.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Lorenz's work placed the concept of *instability* of the Earth's atmosphere onto a quantitative base and linked the concept of instability to the properties of large classes of dynamic systems which are undergoing nonlinear dynamics and deterministic chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The concept of the butterfly effect has since been used outside the context of weather science as a broad term for any situation where a small change is supposed to be the cause of larger consequences.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] In *The Vocation of Man* (1800), Johann Gottlieb Fichte says "you could not remove a single grain of sand from its place without thereby ... changing something throughout all parts of the immeasurable whole".
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Chaos theory and the sensitive dependence on initial conditions were described in numerous forms of literature.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] This is evidenced by the case of the three-body problem by Poincaré in 1890.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] He later proposed that such phenomena could be common, for example, in meteorology.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] In 1898, Jacques Hadamard noted general divergence of trajectories in spaces of negative curvature.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Pierre Duhem discussed the possible general significance of this in 1908.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] In 1961, Lorenz was running a numerical computer model to redo a weather prediction from the middle of the previous run as a shortcut.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] He entered the initial condition 0.506 from the printout instead of entering the full precision 0.506127 value.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The result was a completely different weather scenario.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] In 1963, Lorenz published a theoretical study of this effect in a highly cited, seminal paper called *Deterministic Nonperiodic Flow* (the calculations were performed on a Royal McBee LGP-30 computer).
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Following proposals from colleagues, in later speeches and papers, Lorenz used the more poetic butterfly.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] According to Lorenz, when he failed to provide a title for a talk he was to present at the 139th meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 1972, Philip Merilees concocted *Does the flap of a butterfly's wings in Brazil set off a tornado in Texas?* as a title.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Although a butterfly flapping its wings has remained constant in the expression of this concept, the location of the butterfly, the consequences, and the location of the consequences have varied widely.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The phrase refers to the effect of a butterfly's wings creating tiny changes in the atmosphere that may ultimately alter the path of a tornado or delay, accelerate, or even prevent the occurrence of a tornado in another location.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The flapping wing creates a small change in the initial condition of the system, which cascades to large-scale alterations of events (compare: domino effect).
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Had the butterfly not flapped its wings, the trajectory of the system might have been vastly different—but it's also equally possible that the set of conditions without the butterfly flapping its wings is the set that leads to a tornado.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The butterfly effect presents an obvious challenge to prediction, since initial conditions for a system such as the weather can never be known to complete accuracy.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] This problem motivated the development of ensemble forecasting, in which a number of forecasts are made from perturbed initial conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Some scientists have since argued that the weather system is not as sensitive to initial conditions as previously believed.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] David Orrell argues that the major contributor to weather forecast error is model error, with sensitivity to initial conditions playing a relatively small role.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Stephen Wolfram also notes that the Lorenz equations are highly simplified and do not contain terms that represent viscous effects; he believes that these terms would tend to damp out small perturbations.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Recent studies using generalized Lorenz models that included additional dissipative terms and nonlinearity suggested that a larger heating parameter is required for the onset of chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Lorenz proposed a mathematical model for how tiny motions in the atmosphere scale up to affect larger systems.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] He found that the systems in that model could only be predicted up to a specific point in the future, and beyond that, reducing the error in the initial conditions would not increase the predictability (as long as the error is not zero).
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] This demonstrated that a deterministic system could be "observationally indistinguishable" from a non-deterministic one in terms of predictability.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Recent re-examinations of this paper suggest that it offered a significant challenge to the idea that our universe is deterministic, comparable to the challenges offered by quantum physics.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] In the same book, Lorenz applied the activity of skiing and developed an idealized skiing model for revealing the sensitivity of time-varying paths to initial positions.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] A predictability horizon is determined before the onset of SDIC.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Recurrence, the approximate return of a system toward its initial conditions, together with sensitive dependence on initial conditions, are the two main ingredients for chaotic motion.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] They have the practical consequence of making complex systems, such as the weather, difficult to predict past a certain time range (approximately a week in the case of weather) since it is impossible to measure the starting atmospheric conditions completely accurately.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] A dynamical system displays sensitive dependence on initial conditions if points arbitrarily close together separate over time at an exponential rate.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The definition is not topological, but essentially metrical.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The definition does not require that all points from a neighborhood separate from the base point *x*, but it requires one positive Lyapunov exponent.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] In addition to a positive Lyapunov exponent, boundedness is another major feature within chaotic systems.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] For rational $\theta$ , after a finite number of iterations $x_{n}$ maps into a periodic sequence.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] But almost all $\theta$ are irrational, and, for irrational $\theta$ , $x_{n}$ never repeats itself – it is non-periodic.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The butterfly effect is most familiar in terms of weather; it can easily be demonstrated in standard weather prediction models, for example.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The climate scientists James Annan and William Connolley explain that chaos is important in the development of weather prediction methods; models are sensitive to initial conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] They add the caveat: "Of course the existence of an unknown butterfly flapping its wings has no direct bearing on weather forecasts, since it will take far too long for such a small perturbation to grow to a significant size, and we have many more immediate uncertainties to worry about.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The concept of the butterfly effect encompasses several phenomena.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The two kinds of butterfly effects, including the sensitive dependence on initial conditions, and the ability of a tiny perturbation to create an organized circulation at large distances, are not exactly the same.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] In Palmer et al., a new type of butterfly effect is introduced, highlighting the potential impact of small-scale processes on finite predictability within the Lorenz 1969 model.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Additionally, the identification of ill-conditioned aspects of the Lorenz 1969 model points to a practical form of finite predictability.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] These two distinct mechanisms suggesting finite predictability in the Lorenz 1969 model are collectively referred to as the third kind of butterfly effect.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The authors in have considered Palmer et al.'s suggestions and have aimed to present their perspective without raising specific contentions.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The third kind of butterfly effect with finite predictability, as discussed in, was primarily proposed based on a convergent geometric series, known as Lorenz's and Lilly's formulas.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Ongoing discussions are addressing the validity of these two formulas for estimating predictability limits in.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] A comparison of the two kinds of butterfly effects and the third kind of butterfly effect has been documented.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] In recent studies, it was reported that both meteorological and non-meteorological linear models have shown that instability plays a role in producing a butterfly effect, which is characterized by brief but significant exponential growth resulting from a small disturbance.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The first kind of butterfly effect (BE1), known as SDIC (Sensitive Dependence on Initial Conditions), is widely recognized and demonstrated through idealized chaotic models.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] However, opinions differ regarding the second kind of butterfly effect, specifically the impact of a butterfly flapping its wings on tornado formation, as indicated in two 2024 articles.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] In more recent discussions published by *Physics Today*, it is acknowledged that the second kind of butterfly effect (BE2) has never been rigorously verified using a realistic weather model.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] While the studies suggest that BE2 is unlikely in the real atmosphere, its invalidity in this context does not negate the applicability of BE1 in other areas, such as pandemics or historical events.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] For the third kind of butterfly effect, the limited predictability within the Lorenz 1969 model is explained by scale interactions in one article and by system ill-conditioning in another more recent study.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] According to Lighthill (1986), the presence of SDIC (commonly known as the butterfly effect) implies that chaotic systems have a finite predictability limit.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Recently, a short video has been created to present Lorenz's perspective on predictability limit.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The hypothesis supports the investigation into extended-range predictions using both partial differential equation (PDE)-based physics methods and Artificial Intelligence (AI) techniques.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The potential for sensitive dependence on initial conditions (the butterfly effect) has been studied in a number of cases in semiclassical and quantum physics, including atoms in strong fields and the anisotropic Kepler problem.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] The random matrix theory and simulations with quantum computers prove that some versions of the butterfly effect in quantum mechanics do not exist.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Other authors suggest that the butterfly effect can be observed in quantum systems.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Karkuszewski et al. consider the time evolution of quantum systems which have slightly different Hamiltonians.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] They investigate the level of sensitivity of quantum systems to small changes in their given Hamiltonians.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] David Poulin et al. presented a quantum algorithm to measure fidelity decay, which "measures the rate at which identical initial states diverge when subjected to slightly different dynamics".
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] They consider fidelity decay to be "the closest quantum analog to the (purely classical) butterfly effect".
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Whereas the classical butterfly effect considers the effect of a small change in the position and/or velocity of an object in a given Hamiltonian system, the quantum butterfly effect considers the effect of a small change in the Hamiltonian system with a given initial position and velocity.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] This quantum butterfly effect has been demonstrated experimentally.
[src:chaos-theory/butterfly-effect] Quantum and semiclassical treatments of system sensitivity to initial conditions are known as quantum chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Small differences in initial conditions, such as those due to errors in measurements or due to rounding errors in numerical computation, can yield widely diverging outcomes for such dynamic systems, rendering long-term prediction of their behavior impossible in general.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This can happen even though these systems are deterministic, meaning that their future behavior follows a unique evolution and is fully determined by their initial conditions, with no random elements involved.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In other words, despite the deterministic nature of these systems, this does not make them predictable.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This behavior is known as **deterministic chaos**, or simply **chaos**.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Chaotic behavior exists in many natural systems, including fluid flow, heartbeat irregularities, weather and climate.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] It also occurs spontaneously in some systems with artificial components, such as road traffic.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This behavior can be studied through the analysis of a chaotic mathematical model or through analytical techniques such as recurrence plots and Poincaré maps.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Chaos theory has applications in a variety of disciplines, including meteorology, anthropology, sociology, environmental science, computer science, engineering, economics, ecology, and pandemic crisis management.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The theory formed the basis for such fields of study as complex dynamical systems, edge of chaos theory and self-assembly processes.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Chaos theory concerns deterministic systems which are predictable for some amount of time and then appear to become random.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Some examples of Lyapunov times are: Chaotic electrical circuits, about 1 millisecond; weather systems, a few days (but unproven); the inner solar system, 4 to 5 million years.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In chaotic systems, the uncertainty in a forecast increases exponentially with elapsed time.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Hence, mathematically, doubling the forecast time more than squares the proportional uncertainty in the forecast.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This means, in practice, a meaningful prediction cannot be made over an interval of more than two or three times the Lyapunov time.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] When meaningful predictions cannot be made, the system appears random.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In common usage, "chaos" means "a state of disorder".
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] However, in chaos theory, the term is defined more precisely.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Although no universally accepted mathematical definition of chaos exists, a commonly used definition, originally formulated by Robert L.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In some cases, the last two properties above have been shown to actually imply sensitivity to initial conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In the discrete-time case, this is true for all continuous maps on metric spaces.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In these cases, while it is often the most practically significant property, "sensitivity to initial conditions" need not be stated in the definition.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] If attention is restricted to intervals, the second property implies the other two.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] An alternative and a generally weaker definition of chaos uses only the first two properties in the above list.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The flapping wing represents a small change in the initial condition of the system, which causes a chain of events that prevents the predictability of large-scale phenomena.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Had the butterfly not flapped its wings, the trajectory of the overall system could have been vastly different.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] As suggested in Lorenz's book entitled *The Essence of Chaos*, published in 1993, "sensitive dependence can serve as an acceptable definition of chaos".
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] An idealized skiing model was developed to illustrate the sensitivity of time-varying paths to initial positions.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] A predictability horizon can be determined before the onset of SDIC (i.e., prior to significant separations of initial nearby trajectories).
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] A consequence of sensitivity to initial conditions is that if we start with a limited amount of information about the system (as is usually the case in practice), then beyond a certain time, the system would no longer be predictable.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This is most prevalent in the case of weather, which is generally predictable only about a week ahead.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This does not mean that one cannot assert anything about events far in the future - only that some restrictions on the system are present.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] For example, we know that the temperature of the surface of the earth will not naturally reach 100 °C (212 °F) or fall below −130 °C (−202 °F) on earth (during the current geologic era), but we cannot predict exactly which day will have the hottest temperature of the year.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In more mathematical terms, the Lyapunov exponent measures the sensitivity to initial conditions, in the form of rate of exponential divergence from the perturbed initial conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] where t is the time and $\lambda$ is the Lyapunov exponent.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The rate of separation depends on the orientation of the initial separation vector, so a whole spectrum of Lyapunov exponents can exist.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The number of Lyapunov exponents is equal to the number of dimensions of the phase space, though it is common to just refer to the largest one.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] For example, the maximal Lyapunov exponent (MLE) is most often used, because it determines the overall predictability of the system.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] A positive MLE, coupled with the solution's boundedness, is usually taken as an indication that the system is chaotic.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In addition to the above property, other properties related to sensitivity of initial conditions also exist.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] These include, for example, measure-theoretical mixing (as discussed in ergodic theory) and properties of a K-system.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] A chaotic system may have sequences of values for the evolving variable that exactly repeat themselves, giving periodic behavior starting from any point in that sequence.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] However, such periodic sequences are repelling rather than attracting, meaning that if the evolving variable is outside the sequence, however close, it will not enter the sequence and in fact, will diverge from it.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Thus for almost all initial conditions, the variable evolves chaotically with non-periodic behavior.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Topological mixing (or the weaker condition of topological transitivity) means that the system evolves over time so that any given region or open set of its phase space eventually overlaps with any other given region.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This mathematical concept of "mixing" corresponds to the standard intuition, and the mixing of colored dyes or fluids is an example of a chaotic system.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Topological mixing is often omitted from popular accounts of chaos, which equate chaos with only sensitivity to initial conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] However, sensitive dependence on initial conditions alone does not give chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] For example, consider the simple dynamical system produced by repeatedly doubling an initial value.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This system has sensitive dependence on initial conditions everywhere, since any pair of nearby points eventually becomes widely separated.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] However, this example has no topological mixing, and therefore has no chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Indeed, it has extremely simple behavior: all points except 0 tend to positive or negative infinity.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] A map $f:X\to X$ is said to be topologically transitive if for any pair of non-empty open sets $U,V\subset X$ , there exists $k>0$ such that $f^{k}(U)\cap V\neq \emptyset$ .
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Topological transitivity is a weaker version of topological mixing.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Intuitively, if a map is topologically transitive then given a point *x* and a region *V*, there exists a point *y* near *x* whose orbit passes through *V*.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This implies that it is impossible to decompose the system into two open sets.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] An important related theorem is the Birkhoff Transitivity Theorem.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] It is easy to see that the existence of a dense orbit implies topological transitivity.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The Birkhoff Transitivity Theorem states that if *X* is a second countable, complete metric space, then topological transitivity implies the existence of a dense set of points in *X* that have dense orbits.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] For a chaotic system to have dense periodic orbits means that every point in the space is approached arbitrarily closely by periodic orbits.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The one-dimensional logistic map defined by *x* → 4 *x* (1 – *x*) is one of the simplest systems with density of periodic orbits.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] (indeed, for all the periods specified by Sharkovskii's theorem).
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Sharkovskii's theorem is the basis of the Li and Yorke (1975) proof that any continuous one-dimensional system that exhibits a regular cycle of period three will also display regular cycles of every other length, as well as completely chaotic orbits.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Some dynamical systems, like the one-dimensional logistic map defined by *x* → 4 *x* (1 – *x*), are chaotic everywhere, but in many cases chaotic behavior is found only in a subset of phase space.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The cases of most interest arise when the chaotic behavior takes place on an attractor, since then a large set of initial conditions leads to orbits that converge to this chaotic region.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] An easy way to visualize a chaotic attractor is to start with a point in the basin of attraction of the attractor, and then simply plot its subsequent orbit.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Because of the topological transitivity condition, this is likely to produce a picture of the entire final attractor, and indeed both orbits shown in the figure on the right give a picture of the general shape of the Lorenz attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This attractor results from a simple three-dimensional model of the Lorenz weather system.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The Lorenz attractor is perhaps one of the best-known chaotic system diagrams, probably because it is not only one of the first, but it is also one of the most complex, and as such gives rise to a very interesting pattern that, with a little imagination, looks like the wings of a butterfly.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Unlike fixed-point attractors and limit cycles, the attractors that arise from chaotic systems, known as strange attractors, have great detail and complexity.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Strange attractors occur in both continuous dynamical systems (such as the Lorenz system) and in some discrete systems (such as the Hénon map).
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Other discrete dynamical systems have a repelling structure called a Julia set, which forms at the boundary between basins of attraction of fixed points.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Julia sets can be thought of as strange repellers.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Both strange attractors and Julia sets typically have a fractal structure, and the fractal dimension can be calculated for them.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In contrast to single type chaotic solutions, studies using Lorenz models have emphasized the importance of considering various types of solutions.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] For example, coexisting chaotic and non-chaotic may appear within the same model (e.g., the double pendulum system) using the same modeling configurations but different initial conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The findings of attractor coexistence, obtained from classical and generalized Lorenz models, suggested a revised view that "the entirety of weather possesses a dual nature of chaos and order with distinct predictability", in contrast to the conventional view of "weather is chaotic".
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Discrete chaotic systems, such as the logistic map, can exhibit strange attractors whatever their dimensionality.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In contrast, for continuous dynamical systems, the Poincaré–Bendixson theorem shows that a strange attractor can only arise in three or more dimensions.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Finite-dimensional linear systems are never chaotic; for a dynamical system to display chaotic behavior, it must be either nonlinear or infinite-dimensional.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The Poincaré–Bendixson theorem states that a two-dimensional differential equation has very regular behavior.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] where x , y , and z make up the system state, t is time, and $\sigma$ , $\rho$ , $\beta$ are the system parameters.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Five of the terms on the right hand side are linear, while two are quadratic; a total of seven terms.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Another well-known chaotic attractor is generated by the Rössler equations, which have only one nonlinear term out of seven.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Sprott found a three-dimensional system with just five terms, that had only one nonlinear term, which exhibits chaos for certain parameter values.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Zhang and Heidel showed that, at least for dissipative and conservative quadratic systems, three-dimensional quadratic systems with only three or four terms on the right-hand side cannot exhibit chaotic behavior.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The reason is, simply put, that solutions to such systems are asymptotic to a two-dimensional surface and therefore solutions are well behaved.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] While the Poincaré–Bendixson theorem shows that a continuous dynamical system on the Euclidean plane cannot be chaotic, two-dimensional continuous systems with non-Euclidean geometry can still exhibit some chaotic properties.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The above set of three ordinary differential equations has been referred to as the three-dimensional Lorenz model.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Since 1963, higher-dimensional Lorenz models have been developed in numerous studies for examining the impact of an increased degree of nonlinearity, as well as its collective effect with heating and dissipations, on solution stability.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Perhaps surprisingly, chaos may occur also in linear systems, provided they are infinite dimensional.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] A theory of linear chaos is being developed in functional analysis.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] $f[\psi _{n}({\vec {r}},t)]$ might be logistic map alike $\psi \rightarrow G\psi [1-\tanh(\psi )]$ or complex map.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] When wave propagation problems at distance $L=ct$ with wavelength $\lambda =2\pi /k$ are considered the kernel K may have a form of Green function for Schrödinger equation:.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Under the right conditions, chaos spontaneously evolves into a lockstep pattern.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In the Kuramoto model, four conditions suffice to produce synchronization in a chaotic system.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Examples include the coupled oscillation of Christiaan Huygens' pendulums, fireflies, neurons, the London Millennium Bridge resonance, and large arrays of Josephson junctions.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Moreover, from the theoretical physics standpoint, dynamical chaos itself, in its most general manifestation, is a spontaneous order.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The essence here is that most orders in nature arise from the spontaneous breakdown of various symmetries.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This large family of phenomena includes elasticity, superconductivity, ferromagnetism, and many others.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] According to the supersymmetric theory of stochastic dynamics, chaos, or more precisely, its stochastic generalization, is also part of this family.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The corresponding symmetry being broken is the topological supersymmetry which is hidden in all stochastic (partial) differential equations, and the corresponding order parameter is a field-theoretic embodiment of the butterfly effect.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] There are also definitions of chaos that don't require the sensitivity on initial conditions property, such as combinatorial chaos (I.e. applying recursively a discrete combinatorial action).
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This is also comparable and similar to chaos generated by cellular automata.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This is important because, as this type of chaos can be equivalent to a turing machine, it is possible to execute computation with such dynamical systems, which is an intuitive way to see that the halting problem is not decidable, implying that some computational algorithms may never end.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Unpredictability in this type of system is typically of a different nature than that of other types of chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] James Clerk Maxwell was the first scientist to emphasize the importance of initial conditions, and he is seen as being one of the earliest to discuss chaos theory, with work in the 1860s and 1870s.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In the 1880s, while studying the three-body problem, Henri Poincaré found that there can be orbits that are nonperiodic, and yet not forever increasing nor approaching a fixed point.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In 1898, Jacques Hadamard published an influential study of the motion of a free particle gliding frictionlessly on a surface of constant negative curvature, called "Hadamard's billiards".
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Hadamard was able to show that all trajectories are unstable, in that all particle trajectories diverge exponentially from one another, with a positive Lyapunov exponent.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Later studies, also on the topic of nonlinear differential equations, were carried out by George David Birkhoff, Andrey Nikolaevich Kolmogorov, Mary Lucy Cartwright and John Edensor Littlewood, and Stephen Smale.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Experimentalists and mathematicians had encountered turbulence in fluid motion, chaotic behaviour in society and economy, nonperiodic oscillation in radio circuits and fractal patterns in nature without the benefit of a theory to explain what they were seeing.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Both of these observations underline the connection of chaos to either stochastic or non-linear dynamical systems, but definitely non-differentiable and non-continuous time evolution.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] What had been attributed to measure imprecision and simple "noise" was considered by chaos theorists as a full component of the studied systems.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In 1959 Boris Valerianovich Chirikov proposed a criterion for the emergence of classical chaos in Hamiltonian systems (Chirikov criterion).
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] He applied this criterion to explain some experimental results on plasma confinement in open mirror traps.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This is regarded as the very first physical theory of chaos, which succeeded in explaining a concrete experiment.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] And Boris Chirikov himself is considered as a pioneer in classical and quantum chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The main catalyst for the development of chaos theory was the electronic computer.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Much of the mathematics of chaos theory involves the repeated iteration of simple mathematical formulas, which would be impractical to do by hand.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Electronic computers made these repeated calculations practical, while figures and images made it possible to visualize these systems.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] As a graduate student in Chihiro Hayashi's laboratory at Kyoto University, Yoshisuke Ueda was experimenting with analog computers and noticed, on November 27, 1961, what he called "randomly transitional phenomena".
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Yet his advisor did not agree with his conclusions at the time, and did not allow him to report his findings until 1970.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Edward Lorenz was an early pioneer of the theory.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] His interest in chaos came about accidentally through his work on weather prediction in 1961.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Lorenz and his collaborator Ellen Fetter and Margaret Hamilton were using a simple digital computer, a Royal McBee LGP-30, to run weather simulations.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] They wanted to see a sequence of data again, and to save time they started the simulation in the middle of its course.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] They did this by entering a printout of the data that corresponded to conditions in the middle of the original simulation.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] To their surprise, the weather the machine began to predict was completely different from the previous calculation.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] They tracked this down to the computer printout.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The computer worked with 6-digit precision, but the printout rounded variables off to a 3-digit number, so a value like 0.506127 printed as 0.506.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This difference is tiny, and the consensus at the time would have been that it should have no practical effect.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] However, Lorenz discovered that small changes in initial conditions produced large changes in long-term outcome.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Lorenz's discovery, which gave its name to Lorenz attractors, showed that even detailed atmospheric modeling cannot, in general, make precise long-term weather predictions.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In 1963, Benoit Mandelbrot, studying information theory, discovered that noise in many phenomena (including stock prices and telephone circuits) was patterned like a Cantor set, a set of points with infinite roughness and detail.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Mandelbrot described both the "Noah effect" (in which sudden discontinuous changes can occur) and the "Joseph effect" (in which persistence of a value can occur for a while, yet suddenly change afterwards).
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In 1967, he published "How long is the coast of Britain?
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Statistical self-similarity and fractional dimension", showing that a coastline's length varies with the scale of the measuring instrument, resembles itself at all scales, and is infinite in length for an infinitesimally small measuring device.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Arguing that a ball of twine appears as a point when viewed from far away (0-dimensional), a ball when viewed from fairly near (3-dimensional), or a curved strand (1-dimensional), he argued that the dimensions of an object are relative to the observer and may be fractional.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] An object whose irregularity is constant over different scales ("self-similarity") is a fractal (examples include the Menger sponge, the Sierpiński gasket, and the Koch curve or *snowflake*, which is infinitely long yet encloses a finite space and has a fractal dimension of circa 1.2619).
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In 1982, Mandelbrot published *The Fractal Geometry of Nature*, which became a classic of chaos theory.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In December 1977, the New York Academy of Sciences organized the first symposium on chaos, attended by David Ruelle, Robert May, James A.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Yorke (coiner of the term "chaos" as used in mathematics), Robert Shaw, and the meteorologist Edward Lorenz.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The following year Pierre Coullet and Charles Tresser published "Itérations d'endomorphismes et groupe de renormalisation", and Mitchell Feigenbaum's article "Quantitative Universality for a Class of Nonlinear Transformations" finally appeared in a journal, after 3 years of referee rejections.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Thus Feigenbaum (1975) and Coullet & Tresser (1978) discovered the universality in chaos, permitting the application of chaos theory to many different phenomena.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Libchaber, during a symposium organized in Aspen by Pierre Hohenberg, presented his experimental observation of the bifurcation cascade that leads to chaos and turbulence in Rayleigh–Bénard convection systems.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] He was awarded the Wolf Prize in Physics in 1986 along with Mitchell J.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Feigenbaum for their inspiring achievements.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In 1986, the New York Academy of Sciences co-organized with the National Institute of Mental Health and the Office of Naval Research the first important conference on chaos in biology and medicine.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] There, Bernardo Huberman presented a mathematical model of the eye tracking dysfunction among people with schizophrenia.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This led to a renewal of physiology in the 1980s through the application of chaos theory, for example, in the study of pathological cardiac cycles.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In 1987, Per Bak, Chao Tang and Kurt Wiesenfeld published a paper in *Physical Review Letters* describing for the first time self-organized criticality (SOC), considered one of the mechanisms by which complexity arises in nature.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Alongside largely lab-based approaches such as the Bak–Tang–Wiesenfeld sandpile, many other investigations have focused on large-scale natural or social systems that are known (or suspected) to display scale-invariant behavior.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Given the implications of a scale-free distribution of event sizes, some researchers have suggested that another phenomenon that should be considered an example of SOC is the occurrence of wars.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] These investigations of SOC have included both attempts at modelling (either developing new models or adapting existing ones to the specifics of a given natural system), and extensive data analysis to determine the existence and/or characteristics of natural scaling laws.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Also in 1987 James Gleick published *Chaos: Making a New Science*, which became a best-seller and introduced the general principles of chaos theory as well as its history to the broad public.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Initially the domain of a few, isolated individuals, chaos theory progressively emerged as a transdisciplinary and institutional discipline, mainly under the name of nonlinear systems analysis.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Alluding to Thomas Kuhn's concept of a paradigm shift exposed in *The Structure of Scientific Revolutions* (1962), many "chaologists" (as some described themselves) claimed that this new theory was an example of such a shift, a thesis upheld by Gleick.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The availability of cheaper, more powerful computers broadens the applicability of chaos theory.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Currently, chaos theory remains an active area of research, involving many different disciplines such as mathematics, topology, physics, social systems, population modeling, biology, meteorology, astrophysics, information theory, computational neuroscience, pandemic crisis management, etc.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] For want of a horse, the rider was lost.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] For want of a rider, the battle was lost.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] For want of a battle, the kingdom was lost.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] And all for the want of a horseshoe nail.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Based on the above, many people mistakenly believe that the impact of a tiny initial perturbation monotonically increases with time and that any tiny perturbation can eventually produce a large impact on numerical integrations.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] However, in 2008, Lorenz stated that he did not feel that this verse described true chaos but that it better illustrated the simpler phenomenon of instability and that the verse implicitly suggests that subsequent small events will not reverse the outcome.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Based on the analysis, the verse only indicates divergence, not boundedness.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Boundedness is important for the finite size of a butterfly pattern.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The characteristic of the aforementioned verse was described as "finite-time sensitive dependence".
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Although chaos theory was born from observing weather patterns, it has become applicable to a variety of other situations.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Some areas benefiting from chaos theory today are geology, mathematics, biology, computer science, economics, engineering, finance, meteorology, philosophy, anthropology, physics, politics, population dynamics, and robotics.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] A few categories are listed below with examples, but this is by no means a comprehensive list as new applications are appearing.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Chaos theory has been used for many years in cryptography.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In the past few decades, chaos and nonlinear dynamics have been used in the design of hundreds of cryptographic primitives.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] These algorithms include image encryption algorithms, hash functions, secure pseudo-random number generators, stream ciphers, watermarking, and steganography.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The majority of these algorithms are based on uni-modal chaotic maps and a big portion of these algorithms use the control parameters and the initial condition of the chaotic maps as their keys.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] From a wider perspective, without loss of generality, the similarities between the chaotic maps and the cryptographic systems is the main motivation for the design of chaos based cryptographic algorithms.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] One type of encryption, secret key or symmetric key, relies on diffusion and confusion, which is modeled well by chaos theory.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Another type of computing, DNA computing, when paired with chaos theory, offers a way to encrypt images and other information.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Many of the DNA-Chaos cryptographic algorithms are proven to be either not secure, or the technique applied is suggested to be not efficient.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Robotics is another area that has recently benefited from chaos theory.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Instead of robots acting in a trial-and-error type of refinement to interact with their environment, chaos theory has been used to build a predictive model.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Chaotic dynamics have been exhibited by passive walking biped robots.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] For over a hundred years, biologists have been keeping track of populations of different species with population models.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Most models are continuous, but recently scientists have been able to implement chaotic models in certain populations.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] For example, a study on models of Canadian lynx showed there was chaotic behavior in the population growth.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Chaos can also be found in ecological systems, such as hydrology.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] While a chaotic model for hydrology has its shortcomings, there is still much to learn from looking at the data through the lens of chaos theory.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Another biological application is found in cardiotocography.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Fetal surveillance is a delicate balance of obtaining accurate information while being as noninvasive as possible.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Better models of warning signs of fetal hypoxia can be obtained through chaotic modeling.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] As Perry points out, modeling of chaotic time series in ecology is helped by constraint.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] There is always potential difficulty in distinguishing real chaos from chaos that is only in the model.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Hence both constraint in the model and or duplicate time series data for comparison will be helpful in constraining the model to something close to the reality, for example Perry & Wall 1984.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Gene-for-gene co-evolution sometimes shows chaotic dynamics in allele frequencies.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Adding variables exaggerates this: Chaos is more common in models incorporating additional variables to reflect additional facets of real populations.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] May himself did some of these foundational crop co-evolution studies, and this in turn helped shape the entire field.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Even for a steady environment, merely combining one crop and one pathogen may result in quasi-periodic- or chaotic- oscillations in pathogen population.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] It is possible that economic models can also be improved through an application of chaos theory, but predicting the health of an economic system and what factors influence it most is an extremely complex task.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The empirical literature that tests for chaos in economics and finance presents very mixed results, in part due to confusion between specific tests for chaos and more general tests for non-linear relationships.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Chaos could be found in economics by the means of recurrence quantification analysis.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In fact, Orlando et al. by the means of the so-called recurrence quantification correlation index were able to detect hidden changes in time series.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Then, the same technique was employed to detect transitions from laminar (regular) to turbulent (chaotic) phases as well as differences between macroeconomic variables and highlight hidden features of economic dynamics.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Finally, chaos theory could help in modeling how an economy operates as well as in embedding shocks due to external events such as COVID-19.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Due to the sensitive dependence of solutions on initial conditions (SDIC), also known as the butterfly effect, chaotic systems like the Lorenz 1963 model imply a finite predictability horizon.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This means that while accurate predictions are possible over a finite time period, they are not feasible over an infinite time span.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Considering the nature of Lorenz's chaotic solutions, the committee led by Charney et al. in 1966 extrapolated a doubling time of five days from a general circulation model, suggesting a predictability limit of two weeks.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] This connection between the five-day doubling time and the two-week predictability limit was also recorded in a 1969 report by the Global Atmospheric Research Program (GARP).
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] To acknowledge the combined direct and indirect influences from the Mintz and Arakawa model and Lorenz's models, as well as the leadership of Charney et al., Shen et al. refer to the two-week predictability limit as the "Predictability Limit Hypothesis," drawing an analogy to Moore's Law.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In AI-driven large language models, responses can exhibit sensitivities to factors like alterations in formatting and variations in prompts.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] These sensitivities are akin to butterfly effects.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In chemistry, predicting gas solubility is essential to manufacturing polymers, but models using particle swarm optimization (PSO) tend to converge to the wrong points.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] An improved version of PSO has been created by introducing chaos, which keeps the simulations from getting stuck.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In celestial mechanics, especially when observing asteroids, applying chaos theory leads to better predictions about when these objects will approach Earth and other planets.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Four of the five moons of Pluto rotate chaotically.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In quantum physics and electrical engineering, the study of large arrays of Josephson junctions benefitted greatly from chaos theory.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Closer to home, coal mines have always been dangerous places where frequent natural gas leaks cause many deaths.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Until recently, there was no reliable way to predict when they would occur.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] But these gas leaks have chaotic tendencies that, when properly modeled, can be predicted fairly accurately.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Glass and Mandell and Selz have found that no EEG study has as yet indicated the presence of strange attractors or other signs of chaotic behavior.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Redington and Reidbord (1992) attempted to demonstrate that the human heart could display chaotic traits.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] They monitored the changes in between-heartbeat intervals for a single psychotherapy patient as she moved through periods of varying emotional intensity during a therapy session.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] In their 1995 paper, Metcalf and Allen maintained that they uncovered in animal behavior a pattern of period doubling leading to chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The authors examined a well-known response called schedule-induced polydipsia, by which an animal deprived of food for certain lengths of time will drink unusual amounts of water when the food is at last presented.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The control parameter (r) operating here was the length of the interval between feedings, once resumed.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The authors were careful to test a large number of animals and to include many replications, and they designed their experiment so as to rule out the likelihood that changes in response patterns were caused by different starting places for r.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Time series and first delay plots provide the best support for the claims made, showing a fairly clear march from periodicity to irregularity as the feeding times were increased.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] The various phase trajectory plots and spectral analyses, on the other hand, do not match up well enough with the other graphs or with the overall theory to lead inexorably to a chaotic diagnosis.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] For example, the phase trajectories do not show a definite progression towards greater and greater complexity (and away from periodicity); the process seems quite muddied.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Also, where Metcalf and Allen saw periods of two and six in their spectral plots, there is room for alternative interpretations.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] All of this ambiguity necessitate some serpentine, post-hoc explanation to show that results fit a chaotic model.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] By adapting a model of career counseling to include a chaotic interpretation of the relationship between employees and the job market, Amundson and Bright found that better suggestions can be made to people struggling with career decisions.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Modern organizations are increasingly seen as open complex adaptive systems with fundamental natural nonlinear structures, subject to internal and external forces that may contribute chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] For instance, team building and group development is increasingly being researched as an inherently unpredictable system, as the uncertainty of different individuals meeting for the first time makes the trajectory of the team unknowable.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Traffic forecasting may benefit from applications of chaos theory.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Better predictions of when a congestion will occur would allow measures to be taken to disperse it before it would have occurred.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Combining chaos theory principles with a few other methods has led to a more accurate short-term prediction model, such as the BML traffic model.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Chaos theory has been applied to environmental water cycle data (also hydrological data), such as rainfall and streamflow.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] These studies have yielded controversial results, because the methods for detecting a chaotic signature are often relatively subjective.
[src:chaos-theory/chaos-theory] Early studies tended to "succeed" in finding chaos, whereas subsequent studies and meta-analyses called those studies into question and provided explanations for why these datasets are not likely to have low-dimension chaotic dynamics.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] It is a recurrence relation and a polynomial mapping of degree 2.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] It is often referred to as an archetypal example of how complex, chaotic behaviour can arise from very simple nonlinear dynamical equations.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] The map was initially utilized by Edward Lorenz in the 1960s to showcase properties of irregular solutions in climate systems.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] It was popularized in a 1976 paper by the biologist Robert May, in part as a discrete-time demographic model analogous to the logistic equation written down by Pierre François Verhulst.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] Other researchers who have contributed to the study of the logistic map include Stanisław Ulam, John von Neumann, Pekka Myrberg, Oleksandr Sharkovsky, Nicholas Metropolis, and Mitchell Feigenbaum.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] In the logistic map, *x* is a variable, and *r* is a parameter.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] It can be interpreted as a tool to get next position in the configuration space after one time step.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] The difference equation is a discrete version of the logistic differential equation, which can be compared to a time evolution equation of the system.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] Given an appropriate value for the parameter *r* and performing calculations starting from an initial condition $x_{0}$ , we obtain the sequence $x_{0}$ , $x_{1}$ , $x_{2}$ , ..., which can be interpreted as a sequence of time steps in the evolution of the system.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] In the field of dynamical systems, this sequence is called an orbit, and the orbit changes depending on the value given to the parameter.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] When the parameter is changed, the orbit of the logistic map can change in various ways, such as settling on a single value, repeating several values periodically, or showing non-periodic fluctuations known as chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] This was the initial approach of Henri Poincaré to study dynamical systems and ultimately chaos starting from the study of fixed points or, in other words, states that do not change over time (i.e. when $x_{n}=...=x_{1}=x_{0}=f(x_{0})$ ).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] Many chaotic systems such as the Mandelbrot set emerge from iteration of very simple quadratic nonlinear functions such as the logistic map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] Taking the biological population model as an example xn is a number between zero and one, which represents the ratio of existing population to the maximum possible population.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] The usual values of interest for the parameter r are those in the interval [0, 4], so that xn remains bounded on [0, 1].
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] The *r* = 4 case of the logistic map is a nonlinear transformation of both the bit-shift map and the *μ* = 2 case of the tent map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] If *r* > 4, this leads to negative population sizes.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p01] (This problem does not appear in the older Ricker model, which also exhibits chaotic dynamics.) One can also consider values of r in the interval [−2, 0], so that xn remains bounded on [−0.5, 1.5].
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The animation shows the behaviour of the sequence $x_{n}$ over different values of the parameter r.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] A first observation is that the sequence does not diverge and remains finite for r between 0 and 4.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The first four are also available in standard linear systems, oscillations between two values are available too under resonance, chaotic systems though have typically a large range of resonance conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The other phenomena are peculiar to chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] This progression of stages is strikingly similar to the onset of turbulence.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Chaos is not peculiar to non-linear systems alone and it can also be exhibited by infinite dimensional linear systems.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] As mentioned above, the logistic map itself is an ordinary quadratic function.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] An important question in terms of dynamical systems is how the behavior of the trajectory changes when the parameter r changes.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Depending on the value of r, the behavior of the trajectory of the logistic map can be simple or complex.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Below, we will explain how the behavior of the logistic map changes as r increases.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] As mentioned above, the logistic map can be used as a model to consider the fluctuation of population size.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In this case, the variable x of the logistic map is the number of individuals of an organism divided by the maximum population size, so the possible values of x are limited to 0 ≤ x ≤ 1.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] For this reason, the behavior of the logistic map is often discussed by limiting the range of the variable to the interval [0, 1].
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] If we restrict the variables to 0 ≤ x ≤ 1, then the range of the parameter r is necessarily restricted to 0 to 4 (0 ≤ r ≤ 4).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] This is because if $x_{n}$ is in the range [0, 1], then the maximum value of $x_{n+1}$ is r/4.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Thus, when r > 4, the value of $x_{n+1}$ can exceed 1.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] On the other hand, when r is negative, x can take negative values.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] A graph of the map can also be used to learn much about its behavior.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The graph of the logistic map $x_{n+1}=rx_{n}(1-x_{n})$ is the plane curve that plots the relationship between $x_{n}$ and $x_{n+1}$ , with $x_{n}$ (or x) on the horizontal axis and $x_{n+1}$ (or f (x)) on the vertical axis.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] When r is changed, the vertex moves up or down, and the shape of the parabola changes.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In addition, the parabola of the logistic map intersects with the horizontal axis (the line where $x_{n+1}=0$ ) at two points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The two intersection points are $(x_{n},x_{n+1})=(0,0)$ and $(x_{n},x_{n+1})=(1,0)$ , and the positions of these intersection points are constant and do not depend on the value of r.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Graphs of maps, especially those of one variable such as the logistic map, are key to understanding the behavior of the map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] One of the uses of graphs is to illustrate fixed points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Draw a line y = x (a 45° line) on the graph of the map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] If there is a point where this 45° line intersects with the graph, that point is a fixed point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] It means a point that does not change when the map is applied.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] We will denote the fixed point as $x_{f}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In the case of the logistic map, the fixed point that satisfies equation (2-2) is obtained by solving $rx(1-x)=x$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The concept of fixed points is of primary importance in discrete dynamical systems.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Another graphical technique that can be used for one-variable mappings is the spider web projection.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] After determining an initial value $x_{0}$ on the horizontal axis, draw a vertical line from the initial value $x_{0}$ to the curve of f(x).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Draw a horizontal line from the point where the curve of f(x) meets the 45° line of y = x, and then draw a vertical line from the point where the curve meets the 45° line to the curve of f(x).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] By repeating this process, a spider web or staircase-like diagram is created on the plane.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] This construction is in fact equivalent to calculating the trajectory graphically, and the spider web diagram created represents the trajectory starting from $x_{0}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] This projection allows the overall behavior of the trajectory to be seen at a glance.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The image below shows the amplitude and frequency content of a logistic map that iterates itself for parameter values ranging from 2 to 4.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Again one can see initial linear behaviours then chaotic behaviour not only in the time domain (left) but especially in the frequency domain or spectrum (right), i.e. chaos is present at all scales as it is in the case of Energy cascade of Kolmogorov and it even propagates from one scale to another.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] First, when the parameter r = 0, $x_{1}=0$ , regardless of the initial value $x_{0}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In other words, the trajectory of the logistic map when a = 0 is a trajectory in which all values after the initial value are 0, so there is not much to investigate in this case.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Next, when the parameter r is in the range 0 < r < 1, $x_{n}$ decreases monotonically for any value of $x_{0}$ between 0 and 1.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] That is, $x_{n}$ converges to 0 in the limit n → ∞.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The point to which $x_{n}$ converges is the fixed point $x_{f1}$ shown in equation (2-3).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Fixed points of this type, where orbits around them converge, are called asymptotically stable, stable, or attractive.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Conversely, if orbits around $x_{f}$ move away from $x_{f}$ as time n increases, the fixed point $x_{f}$ is called unstable or repulsive.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] A common and simple way to know whether a fixed point is asymptotically stable is to take the derivative of the map f.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] This derivative is expressed as $f'(x)$ , $x_{f}$ is asymptotically stable if the following condition is satisfied.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] This can be seen by graphing the map: if the slope of the tangent to the curve at $x_{f}$ is between −1 and 1, then $x_{f}$ is stable and the orbit around it is attracted to $x_{f}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] However, the discrimination method using equation (3-1) does not know the range of orbits from $x_{f}$ that are attracted to $x_{f}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] It only guarantees that x within a certain neighborhood of $x_{f}$ will converge.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In this case, the domain of initial values that converge to 0 is the entire domain [0, 1], but to know this for certain, a separate study is required.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The method for determining whether a fixed point is unstable can be found by similarly differentiating the map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] If the parameter lies in the range 0 < r < 1, then the other fixed point $x_{f2}=1-1/a$ is negative and therefore does not lie in the range [0, 1], but it does exist as an unstable fixed point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In the general case with r between 1 and 2, the population will quickly approach the value ⁠*r* − 1/*r*⁠, independent of the initial population.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] When the parameter r = 1, the trajectory of the logistic map converges to 0 as before, but the convergence speed is slower at r = 1.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The fixed point 0 at r = 1 is asymptotically stable, but does not satisfy equation (3-1).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In fact, the discrimination method based on equation (3-1) works by approximating the map to the first order near the fixed point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] When r = 1, this approximation does not hold, and stability or instability is determined by the quadratic (square) terms of the map, or in order words the second order perturbation.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] When r = 1 is graphed, the curve is tangent to the 45° diagonal at x = 0.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In this case, the fixed point $x_{f2}=1-1/r$ , which exists in the negative range for $0<r<1$ , is $x_{f2}=0$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] For $x_{f2}=0$ , that is, as r increases, the value of $x_{f2}$ approaches 0, and just at r = 1 , $x_{f2}$ collides with $x_{f1}=0$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] This collision gives rise to a phenomenon known as a transcritical bifurcation.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Bifurcation is a term used to describe a qualitative change in the behavior of a dynamical system.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In this case, transcritical bifurcation is when the stability of fixed points alternates between each other.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] That is, when r is less than 1, $x_{f1}$ is stable and $x_{f2}$ is unstable, but when r is greater than 1, $x_{f1}$ is unstable and $x_{f2}$ is stable.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The parameter values at which bifurcation occurs are called bifurcation points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In this case, r = 1 is the bifurcation point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] As a result of the bifurcation, the orbit of the logistic map converges to the limit point $x_{f2}=1-1/r$ instead of $x_{f1}=0$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In particular, if the parameter $1<r\leq 2$ , then the trajectory starting from a value $x_{0}$ in the interval (0, 1), exclusive of 0 and 1, converges to $x_{f2}$ by increasing or decreasing monotonically.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In the case of $1-1/r<x_{0}<1/r$ Then, it converges monotonically, $1/r<x_{0}<1$ , the function converges monotonically except for the first step.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Furthermore, the fixed point $x_{f1}=0$ becomes unstable due to bifurcation, but continues to exist as a fixed point even after r > 1.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] This does not mean that there is no initial value other than $x_{f1}$ itself that can reach this unstable fixed point $x_{f1}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] This is $x_{0}=1$ , and since the logistic map satisfies f (1) = 0 regardless of the value of r, applying the map once to $x_{0}=1$ maps it to $x_{f1}=0$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] A point such as x = 1 that can be reached directly as a fixed point by a finite number of iterations of the map is called a final fixed point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] With r between 2 and 3, the population will also eventually approach the same value ⁠*r* − 1/*r*⁠, but first will fluctuate around that value for some time.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The rate of convergence is linear, except for *r* = 3, when it is dramatically slow, less than linear (see Bifurcation memory).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] When the parameter 2 < r < 3, except for the initial values 0 and 1, the fixed point $x_{f2}=1-1/r$ is the same as when 1 < r ≤ 2.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] However, in this case the convergence is not monotonic.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] As the variable approaches $x_{f2}$ , it becomes larger and smaller than $x_{f2}$ repeatedly, and follows a convergent trajectory that oscillates around $x_{f2}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In general, bifurcation diagrams are useful for understanding bifurcations.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] These diagrams are graphs of fixed points (or periodic points, as described below) x as a function of a parameter a, with a on the horizontal axis and x on the vertical axis.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] To distinguish between stable and unstable fixed points, the former curves are sometimes drawn as solid lines and the latter as dotted lines.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In the general case With r between 3 and 1 + √6 ≈ 3.44949 the population will approach permanent oscillations between two values.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] When the parameter is exactly r = 3, the orbit also has a fixed point $x_{f2}=1-1/r$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] However, the variables converge more slowly than when $2<r<3$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] When $r=3$ , the derivative $f'(x_{f2})$ reaches −1 and no longer satisfies equation (3-1).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] When r exceeds 3, $f'(x_{f2})<-1$ , and $x_{f2}$ becomes an unstable fixed point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] That is, another bifurcation occurs at $r=3$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] For $r=3$ a type of bifurcation known as a period doubling bifurcation occurs.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] For $r>3$ , the orbit no longer converges to a single point, but instead alternates between large and small values even after a sufficient amount of time has passed.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Spider diagram and time series for a = 3.3.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The orbit is attracted to a stable 2-periodic point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] An orbit that cycles through the same values periodically is called a periodic orbit.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In this case, the final behavior of the variable as n → ∞ is a periodic orbit with two periods.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Each value (point) that makes up a periodic orbit is called a periodic point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] This gives us the following fourth-order equation.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The solutions of this equation are the periodic points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Therefore, of the solutions to equation (3-5), two correspond to $x_{f1}$ and $x_{f2}$ , and the remaining two solutions are 2-periodic points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] A similar theory about the stability of fixed points can also be applied to periodic points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] That is, a periodic point that attracts surrounding orbits is called an asymptotically stable periodic point, and a periodic point where the surrounding orbits move away is called an unstable periodic point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] It is possible to determine the stability of periodic points in the same way as for fixed points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In the general case, consider $f^{k}(x)$ after k iterations of the map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] then $x_{f}^{(k)}$ is asymptotically stable.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The above discussion of the stability of periodic points can be easily understood by drawing a graph, just like the fixed points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] In this diagram, the horizontal axis is xn and the vertical axis is $x_{n+2}$ , and a curve is drawn that shows the relationship between $x_{n+2}$ and $x_{n}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The intersections of this curve and the 45° line are points that satisfy equation (3-4), so the intersections represent fixed points and 2-periodic points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] If we draw a graph of the logistic map $f^{2}(x)$ , we can observe that the slope of the tangent at the fixed point $x_{f2}$ exceeds 1 at the boundary $r=3$ and becomes unstable.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] At the same time, two new intersections appear, which are the periodic points $x_{f1}^{(2)}$ and $x_{f2}^{(2)}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] when r = 2.7, before the period doubling bifurcation occurs.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] is exactly 1, and a period doubling bifurcation occurs.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] It can be seen that the 2-periodic points are asymptotically stable when this range is $3<r<1+{\sqrt {6}}$ , i.e., when r exceeds $1+{\sqrt {6}}=3.44949...$ , the 2-periodic points are no longer asymptotically stable and their behavior changes.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Almost all initial values in [0, 1] are attracted to the 2-periodic points, but $x_{f1}=0$ and $x_{f2}=1-1/a$ remains as an unstable fixed point in [0,1].
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] These unstable fixed points continue to remain in [0,1] even if r is increased.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Therefore, when the initial value is exactly $x_{f1}$ or $x_{f2}$ , the orbit does not attract to a 2-periodic point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] Moreover, when the initial value is the final fixed point for $x_{f1}$ or the final fixed point for $x_{f2}$ , the orbit does not attract to a 2-periodic point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] There are an infinite number of such final fixed points in [0, 1].
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] However, the number of such points is negligibly small compared to the set of real numbers [ 0, 1].
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] With r between 3.44949 and 3.54409 (approximately), from almost all initial conditions the population will approach permanent oscillations among four values.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The latter number is a root of a 12th degree polynomial (sequence A086181 in the OEIS).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] With r increasing beyond 3.54409, from almost all initial conditions the population will approach oscillations among 8 values, then 16, 32, etc.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] The lengths of the parameter intervals that yield oscillations of a given length decrease rapidly; the ratio between the lengths of two successive bifurcation intervals approaches the Feigenbaum constant *δ* ≈ 4.66920.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] This behavior is an example of a period-doubling cascade.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] When the parameter r exceeds $1+{\sqrt {6}}=3.44949...$ , the previously stable 2-periodic points become unstable, stable 4-periodic points are generated, and the orbit gravitates toward a 4-periodic oscillation.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p02] That is, a period-doubling bifurcation occurs again at $r=3.44949...$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] satisfies, so that solving this equation allows the values of x at the 4-periodic points to be found.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] However, equation (3-11) is a 16th-order equation, and even if we factor out the four solutions for the fixed points and the 2-periodic points, it is still a 12th-order equation.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Therefore, it is no longer possible to solve this equation to obtain an explicit function of a that represents the values of the 4-periodic points in the same way as for the 2-periodic points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] As a becomes larger, the stable 4-periodic point undergoes another period doubling, resulting in a stable 8-periodic point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] As an increases, period doubling bifurcations occur infinitely: 16, 32, 64, ..., and so on, until an infinite period, i.e., an orbit that never returns to its original value.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This infinite series of period doubling bifurcations is called a cascade.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] While these period doubling bifurcations occur infinitely, the intervals between a at which they occur decrease in a geometric progression.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Thus, an infinite number of period doubling bifurcations occur before the parameter a reaches a finite value.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Let the bifurcation from period 1 to period 2 that occurs at r = 3 be counted as the first period doubling bifurcation.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Then, in this cascade of period doubling bifurcations, a stable 2k-periodic point occurs at the k-th bifurcation point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Let the k-th bifurcation point a be denoted as a k.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In this case, it is known that $r_{k}$ converges to the following value as k → ∞.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Furthermore, it is known that the rate of decrease of a k reaches a constant value in the limit, as shown in the following equation.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This value of δ is called the Feigenbaum constant because it was discovered by mathematical physicist Mitchell Feigenbaum. $r_{\infty }$ is called the Feigenbaum point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In the period doubling cascade, $f^{m}$ and $f^{2m}$ have the property that they are locally identical after an appropriate scaling transformation.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The Feigenbaum constant can be found by a technique called renormalization that exploits this self-similarity.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The properties that the logistic map exhibits in the period doubling cascade are also universal in a broader class of maps, as will be discussed later.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] To get an overview of the final behavior of an orbit for a certain parameter, an approximate bifurcation diagram, orbital diagram, is useful.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In this diagram, the horizontal axis is the parameter r and the vertical axis is the variable x, as in the bifurcation diagram.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Using a computer, the parameters are determined and, for example, 500 iterations are performed.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Then, the first 100 results are ignored and only the results of the remaining 400 are plotted.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This allows the initial transient behavior to be ignored and the asymptotic behavior of the orbit remains.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] For example, when one point is plotted for r, it is a fixed point, and when m points are plotted for r, it corresponds to an m-periodic orbit.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When an orbital diagram is drawn for the logistic map, it is possible to see how the branch representing the stable periodic orbit splits, which represents a cascade of period-doubling bifurcations.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When the parameter $r=r_{\infty }$ is exactly the accumulation point of the period-doubling cascade, the variable $x_{n}$ is attracted to aperiodic orbits that never close.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In other words, there exists a periodic point with infinite period at $r_{\infty }$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This aperiodic orbit is called the Feigenbaum attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] An attractor is a term used to refer to a region that has the property of attracting surrounding orbits, and is the orbit that is eventually drawn into and continues.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The attractive fixed points and periodic points mentioned above are also members of the attractor family.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The structure of the Feigenbaum attractor is the same as that of a fractal figure called the Cantor set.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The number of points that compose the Feigenbaum attractor is infinite and their cardinality is equal to the real numbers.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] However, no matter which two of the points are chosen, there is always an unstable periodic point between them, and the distribution of the points is not continuous.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The fractal dimension of the Feigenbaum attractor, the Hausdorff dimension or capacity dimension, is known to be approximately 0.54.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] For any value of r there is at most one stable cycle.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] If a stable cycle exists, it is globally stable, attracting almost all points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Some values of r with a stable cycle of some period have infinitely many unstable cycles of various periods.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The bifurcation diagram at rightabove summarizes this.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The horizontal axis shows the possible values of the parameter r while the vertical axis shows the set of values of x visited asymptotically from almost all initial conditions by the iterates of the logistic equation with that r value.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The bifurcation diagram is a self-similar: if we zoom in on the above-mentioned value *r* ≈ 3.82843 and focus on one arm of the three, the situation nearby looks like a shrunk and slightly distorted version of the whole diagram.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The same is true for all other non-chaotic points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This is an example of the deep and ubiquitous connection between chaos and fractals.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Chaotic orbits of the logistic map when r = 3.82.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When the parameter r exceeds $r_{\infty }=3.56994...$ , the logistic map exhibits chaotic behavior.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Roughly speaking, chaos is a complex and irregular behavior that occurs despite the fact that the difference equation describing the logistic map has no probabilistic ambiguity and the next state is completely and uniquely determined.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The range of $r>r_{\infty }$ of the logistic map is called the chaotic region.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] One of the properties of chaos is its unpredictability, symbolized by the term butterfly effect.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This is due to the property of chaos that a slight difference in the initial state can lead to a huge difference in the later state.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In terms of a discrete dynamical system, if we have two initial values $x_{0}$ and ${\hat {x}}_{0}$ No matter how close they are, once time n has progressed to a certain extent, each destination $x_{n}$ and ${\hat {x}}_{n}$ can vary significantly.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] For example, use $r=3.95,x_{0}=0.1,{\hat {x}}_{0}=x_{0}+10^{-9}$ If the orbits are calculated using two very similar initial values, 0 = 0.1000000001, the difference grows to macroscopic values that are clearly visible on the graph after about 29 iterations.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This property of chaos, called initial condition sensitivity, can be quantitatively expressed by the Lyapunov exponent.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This λ is the distance between the two orbits ( $x_{n}$ and ${\hat {x}}_{n}$ ).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] A positive value of λ indicates that the system is sensitive to initial conditions, while a zero or negative value indicates that the system is not sensitive to initial conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When calculating λ of numerically, it can be confirmed λ remains in the range of zero or negative values in the range $r<r_{\infty }$ , and that λ can take positive values in the range $r>r_{\infty }$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Even beyond $r_{\infty }$ , the behavior does not depend simply on the parameter r.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Many sophisticated mathematical structures lurk in the chaotic region for $r>r_{\infty }$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In this region, chaos does not persist forever; stable periodic orbits reappear.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The region of stable periodic points that exists for r $r_{\infty }<r\leq 4$ is called a periodic window, or simply a window.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] If one looks at a chaotic region in an orbital diagram, the region of nonperiodic orbits looks like a cloud of countless points, with the windows being the scattered blanks surrounded by the cloud.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In each window, the cascade of period-doubling bifurcations that occurred before $r_{\infty }=3.56994...$ occurs again.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] However, instead of the previous stable periodic orbits of 2^k, new stable periodic orbits such as 3×2^k and 5×2^k are generated.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The first window has a period of p, and the windows from which the period-doubling cascade occurs are called windows of period p, etc..
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] For example, a window of period 3 exists in the region around 3.8284 < a < 3.8415, and within this region the period doublings are: 3, 6, 12, 24, ..., 3×2^k, ....
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In the window region, chaos does not disappear but exists in the background.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] However, this chaos is unstable, so only stable periodic orbits are observed.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In the window region, this potential chaos appears before the orbit is attracted from its initial state to a stable periodic orbit.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In this potential presence of chaos, windows differ from the periodic orbits that appeared before a∞.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] There are an infinite number of windows in the range a∞ < a < 4.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The windows have various periods, and there is a window with a period for every natural number greater than or equal to three.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] However, each window does not occur exactly once.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The larger the value of p, the more often a window with that period occurs.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] A window with period 3 occurs only once, while a window with period 13 occurs 315 times.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When a periodic orbit of 3 occurs in the window with period 3, the Szarkovsky order is completed, and all orbits with all periods have been seen.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This formula was derived for p to be a prime number, but in fact it is possible to calculate with good accuracy the number of stable p- periodic points for non-prime p as well.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The window width (the difference between a where the window begins and a where the window ends) is widest for windows with period 3 and narrows for larger periods.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] For example, the window width for a window with period 13 is about 3.13 × 10−6.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Rough estimates suggest that about 10% of $[r_{\infty },4]$ is in the window region, with the rest dominated by chaotic orbits.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The change from chaos to a window as r is increased is caused by a tangent bifurcation, where the map curve is tangent to the diagonal of y = x at the moment of bifurcation, and further parameter changes result in two fixed points where the curve and the line intersect.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] For a window of period p, the iterated map $f^{p}(x)$ exhibits tangent bifurcation, resulting in stable p-periodic orbits.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The exact value of the bifurcation point for a window of period 3 is known, and if the value of this bifurcation point r is $r_{3}$ , then $r_{3}=1+{\sqrt {8}}=3.828427...$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The outline of this bifurcation can be understood by considering the graph of $f^{3}(x)$ (vertical axis $x_{n+3}$ , horizontal axis $x_{n}$ ).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The graph is not tangent except at the fixed points, and there are no 3-periodic points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When a is exactly 3, the graph touches the diagonal at exactly three points, resulting in three periodic points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When a is slightly greater than 3, the graph passes the diagonal and splits into stable and unstable 3-periodic points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When we look at the behavior of $x_{n}$ when r = 3.8282, which is slightly smaller than the branch point $r_{3}$ , we can see that in addition to the irregular changes, there is also a behavior that changes periodically with approximately three periods, and these occur alternately.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This type of periodic behavior is called a "laminar", and the irregular behavior is called a burst, in analogy with fluids.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] There is no regularity in the length of the time periods of the bursts and laminars, and they change irregularly.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] However, when we observe the behavior at r = 3.828327, which is closer to $r_{3}$ , the average length of the laminars is longer and the average length of the bursts is shorter than when r = 3.8282.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] If we further increase r, the length of the laminars becomes larger and larger, and at $r_{3}$ it changes to a perfect three- period.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The phenomenon in which orderly motions called laminars and disorderly motions called bursts occur intermittently is called intermittency or intermittent chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] If we consider the parameter a decreasing from a3, this is a type of emergence of chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] As the parameter moves away from the window, bursts become more dominant, eventually resulting in a completely chaotic state.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This is also a general route to chaos, like the period doubling bifurcation route mentioned above, and routes characterized by the emergence of intermittent chaos due to tangent bifurcations are called intermittency routes.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The mechanism of intermittency can also be understood from the graph of the map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When r is slightly smaller than $r_{3}$ , there is a very small gap between the graph of $f^{3}(x)$ and the diagonal.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This gap is called a channel, and many iterations of the map occur as the orbit passes through the narrow channel.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] During the passage through this channel, $x_{n}$ and $x_{n+3}$ become very close, and the variables change almost like a periodic three orbit.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The orbit eventually leaves the narrow channel, but returns to the channel again as a result of the global structure of the map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] While leaving the channel, it behaves chaotically.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Looking at the entire chaotic domain, whether it is chaotic or windowed, the maximum and minimum values on the vertical axis of the orbital diagram (the upper and lower limits of the attractor) are limited to a certain range.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] As shown in equation (2-1), the maximum value of the logistic map is given by r/4, which is the upper limit of the attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The lower limit of the attractor is given by the point f(r/4) where r/4 is mapped.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Finally, for r = 4, the orbit spans the entire range [0, 1].
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When observing an orbital map, the distribution of points has a characteristic shading.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Darker areas indicate that the variable takes on values in the vicinity of the darker areas, whereas lighter areas indicate that the variable takes on values in the vicinity of the darker areas.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] These differences in the frequency of the points are due to the shape of the graph of the logistic map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The top of the graph, near r/4, attracts orbits with high frequency, and the area near f(r/4) that is mapped from there also becomes highly frequent, and the area near $f^{2}(r/4)$ that is mapped from there also becomes highly frequent, and so on.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The density distribution of points generated by the map is characterized by a quantity called an invariant measure or distribution function, and the invariant measure of the attractor is reproducible regardless of the initial value.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Looking at the beginning of the chaotic region of the orbit diagram, just beyond the accumulation point $r_{\infty }=3.56994$ of the first period - doubling cascade, one can see that the orbit is divided into several subregions.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When there are multiple bands, the orbit moves through each band in a regular order, but the values within each band are irregular.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Such chaotic orbits are called band chaos or periodic chaos, and chaos with k bands is called k -band chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Two-band chaos lies in the range 3.590 < r < 3.675, approximately.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] spacing rapidly decreases, it is not possible to show more than eight bands.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The top and bottom lines, which contain the orbitals, are within the range of equation (3-16).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] As the value of r is further decreased from the left-hand end of two-band chaos, r = 3.590, the number of bands doubles, just as in the period doubling bifurcation.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Let $e_{p}$ (for p = 1, 2, 4, ..., 2k, ...) denote the bifurcation points where p − 1 band chaos splits into p band chaos, or where p band chaos merges into p − 1 band chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Then, just as in the period doubling bifurcation, e p accumulates to a value as p → ∞.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] At this accumulation point $e_{\infty }$ , the number of bands becomes infinite, and the value of $e_{\infty }$ is equal to the value of $r_{\infty }$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Similarly, for the bifurcation points of the period-doubling bifurcation cascade that appeared before a∞, let a p (where p = 1, 2, 4, ..., 2k, ...) denote the bifurcation points where p stable periodic orbits branch into p + 1 stable periodic orbits.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In this case, if we look at the orbital diagram from $r_{2}$ to $e_{2}$ , there are two reduced versions of the global orbital diagram from $r_{1}$ to $e_{1}$ in the orbital diagram from $r_{2}$ to $e_{2}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Similarly, if we look at the orbital diagram from $r_{4}$ to $e_{4}$ , there are four reduced versions of the global orbital diagram from a1 to e1 in the orbital diagram from $r_{4}$ to $e_{4}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Similarly, there are p reduced versions of the global orbital diagram in the orbital diagram from ap to ep, and the branching structure of the logistic map has an infinite self-similar hierarchy.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] A self-similar hierarchy of bifurcation structures also exists within windows.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The period-doubling bifurcation cascades within a window follow the same path as the cascades of period-2k bifurcations.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] That is, there are an infinite number of period-doubling bifurcations within a window, after which the behavior becomes chaotic again.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] For example, in a window of period 3, the cascade of stable periodic orbits ends at $a_{3\infty }$ ≈ 3.8495.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] After $a_{3\infty }$ ≈ 3.8495, the behavior becomes band chaos of multiples of three.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] As a increases from $a_{3\infty }$ , these band chaos also merge by twos, until at the end of the window there are three bands.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Within such bands within a window, there are an infinite number of windows.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Ultimately, the window contains a miniature version of the entire orbital diagram for 1 ≤ a ≤ 4, and within the window there exists a self-similar hierarchy of branchings.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] At the end of the window, the system reverts to widespread chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] For a period 3 window, the final 3-band chaos turns into large-area 1-band chaos at a ≈ 3.857, ending the window.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] However, this change is discontinuous, and the 3-band chaotic attractor suddenly changes size and turns into a 1-band.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Such discontinuous changes in attractor size are called crises.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Crises of this kind, which occur at the end of a window, are also called internal crises.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When a crisis occurs at the end of a window, a stable periodic orbit just touches an unstable periodic point that is not visible on the orbit diagram.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This creates an exit point through which the periodic orbits can escape, resulting in an internal crisis.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Immediately after the internal crisis, there are periods of widespread chaos, and periods of time when the original band chaotic behavior reoccurs, resulting in a kind of intermittency similar to that observed at the beginning of a window.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When the parameter r = 4, the behavior becomes chaotic over the entire range [0, 1].
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] At this time, the Lyapunov exponent λ is maximized, and the state is the most chaotic.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The value of λ for the logistic map at r = 4 can be calculated precisely, and its value is λ = log 2.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Although a strict mathematical definition of chaos has not yet been unified, it can be shown that the logistic map with r = 4 is chaotic on [0, 1] according to one well-known definition of chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Here, ρ(x) means that the fraction of points xn that fall in the infinitesimal interval [x,x+dx] when the map is iterated is given by ρ(x) dx.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The frequency distribution of the logistic map with r = 4 has high density near both sides of [0, 1] and is least dense at x = 0.5.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When r = 4, apart from chaotic orbits, there are also periodic orbits with any period.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] For a natural number n, the graph of $f_{r=4}^{n}(x)$ is a curve with $2^{n-1}$ peaks and $2^{n-1}-1$ valleys, all of which are tangent to 0 and 1.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Thus, the number of intersections between the diagonal and the graph is $2^{n}$ , and there are $2^{n}$ fixed points of $f^{n}(x)$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The n-periodic points are always included in these $2^{n}$ fixed points, so any n-periodic orbit exists for $f_{r=4}^{n}(x)$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Thus, when r = 4, there are an infinite number of periodic points on [0, 1], but all of these periodic points are unstable.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Furthermore, the uncountably infinite set in the interval [0, 1], the number of periodic points is countably infinite, and so almost all orbits starting from initial values are not periodic but non-periodic.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] One of the important aspects of chaos is its dual nature: deterministic and stochastic.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Dynamical systems are deterministic processes, but when the range of variables is appropriately coarse-grained, they become indistinguishable from stochastic processes.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In the case of the logistic map with r = 4, the outcome of every coin toss can be described by the trajectory of the logistic map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Assume that a coin is tossed with a probability of 1/2 landing on heads or tails, and the coin is tossed repeatedly.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] If heads is 0 and tails is 1, then the result of heads, tails, heads, tails, etc. will be a symbol string such as 01001....
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] On the other hand, for the trajectory $x_{0},x_{1},x_{2},...$ of the logistic map, values less than x = 0.5 are converted to 0 and values greater than x = 0.5 are converted to 1, and the trajectory is replaced with a symbol string consisting of 0s and 1s.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Let $S_{C}$ be the symbol string resulting from the former coin toss, and $S_{L}$ be the symbol string resulting from the latter logistic map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The symbols in the symbol string $S_{C}$ were determined by random coin tossing, so any number sequence patterns are possible.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] So, whatever the string $S_{L}$ of the logistic map, there is an identical one in $S_{C}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] And, what is "remarkable" is that the converse is also true: whatever the string of $S_{C}$ , it can be realized by a logistic map trajectory $S_{L}$ by choosing the appropriate initial values.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] When the parameter r exceeds 4, the vertex r /4 of the logistic map graph exceeds 1.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] To the extent that the graph penetrates 1, trajectories can escape [0, 1].
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The bifurcation at r = 4 is also a type of crisis, specifically a boundary crisis.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In this case, the attractor at [0, 1] becomes unstable and collapses, and since there is no attractor outside it, the trajectory diverges to infinity.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] On the other hand, there are orbits that remain in [0, 1] even if r > 4.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Easy-to-understand examples are fixed points and periodic points in [0, 1], which remain in [0, 1].
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] However, there are also orbits that remain in [0, 1] other than fixed points and periodic points.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Let $A_{0}$ be the interval of x such that f (x) > 1.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] As mentioned above, once a variable $x_{n}$ enters $A_{0}$ , it diverges to minus infinity.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] There is also $r_{n}$ x in [0, 1] that maps to $A_{0}$ after one application of the map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This interval of x is divided into two, which are collectively called $A_{1}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Similarly, there are four intervals that map to $A_{1}$ after one application of the map, which are collectively called $A_{2}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Similarly, there are 2n intervals $A_{n}$ that reach $A_{0}$ after n iterations.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Therefore, the interval $\Lambda$ obtained by removing $A_{n}$ from [0, 1] an infinite number of times as follows is a collection of orbits that remain in I.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The process of removing $A_{n}$ from [0, 1] is similar to the construction of the Cantor set mentioned above, and in fact Λ exists in [0, 1] as a Cantor set (a closed, completely disconnected, and complete subset of [0, 1]).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Furthermore, on $\Lambda$ , the logistic map $f_{r>4}$ is chaotic.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Since the logistic map has been often studied as an ecological model, the case where the parameter r is negative has rarely been discussed.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] As a decreases from 0, when −1 < r < 0, the map asymptotically approaches a stable fixed point of xf = 0, but when a exceeds −1, it bifurcates into two periodic points, and as in the case of positive values, it passes through a period doubling bifurcation and reaches chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Finally, when a falls below −2, the map diverges to plus infinity.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Orbit diagram for parameter r from −2 to 4.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The orbit diverges when the parameter a goes beyond this range, both on the negative and positive sides.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] For a logistic map with a specific parameter a , an exact solution that explicitly includes the time n and the initial value $x_{0}$ has been obtained as follows.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The relative simplicity of the logistic map makes it a widely used point of entry into a consideration of the concept of chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] These are properties of the logistic map for most values of r between about 3.57 and 4 (as noted above).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] A common source of such sensitivity to initial conditions is that the map represents a repeated folding and stretching of the space on which it is defined.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In the case of the logistic map, the quadratic difference equation describing it may be thought of as a stretching-and-folding operation on the interval (0,1).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The following figure illustrates the stretching and folding over a sequence of iterates of the map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Figure (a), left, shows a two-dimensional Poincaré plot of the logistic map's state space for *r* = 4, and clearly shows the quadratic curve of the difference equation (**1**).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] However, we can embed the same sequence in a three-dimensional state space, in order to investigate the deeper structure of the map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Figure (b) demonstrates this, showing how initially nearby points begin to diverge, particularly in those regions of xt corresponding to the steeper sections of the plot.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This stretching-and-folding does not just produce a gradual divergence of the sequences of iterates, but an exponential divergence (see Lyapunov exponents), evidenced also by the complexity and unpredictability of the chaotic logistic map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In fact, exponential divergence of sequences of iterates explains the connection between chaos and unpredictability: a small error in the supposed initial state of the system will tend to correspond to a large error later in its evolution.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Hence, predictions about future states become progressively (indeed, exponentially) worse when there are even very small errors in our knowledge of the initial state.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This quality of unpredictability and apparent randomness led the logistic map equation to be used as a pseudo-random number generator in early computers.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] At r = 2, the function $rx(1-x)$ intersects $y=x$ precisely at the maximum point, so convergence to the equilibrium point is on the order of $\delta ^{2^{n}}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Consequently, the equilibrium point is called "superstable".
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] A similar argument shows that there is a superstable r value within each interval where the dynamical system has a stable cycle.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This can be seen in the Lyapunov exponent plot as sharp dips.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Since the map is confined to an interval on the real number line, its dimension is less than or equal to unity.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Numerical estimates yield a correlation dimension of 0.500±0.005 (Grassberger, 1983), a Hausdorff dimension of about 0.538 (Grassberger 1981), and an information dimension of approximately 0.5170976 (Grassberger 1983) for *r* ≈ 3.5699456 (onset of chaos).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Note: It can be shown that the correlation dimension is certainly between 0.4926 and 0.5024.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] It is often possible, however, to make precise and accurate statements about the *likelihood* of a future state in a chaotic system.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] If a (possibly chaotic) dynamical system has an attractor, then there exists a probability measure that gives the long-run proportion of time spent by the system in the various regions of the attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] In the case of the logistic map with parameter *r* = 4 and an initial state in (0,1), the attractor is also the interval (0,1) and the probability measure corresponds to the beta distribution with parameters *a* = 0.5 and *b* = 0.5.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Unpredictability is not randomness, but in some circumstances looks very much like it.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Hence, and fortunately, even if we know very little about the initial state of the logistic map (or some other chaotic system), we can still say something about the distribution of states arbitrarily far into the future, and use this knowledge to inform decisions based on the state of the system.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Although exact solutions to the recurrence relation are only available in a small number of cases, a closed-form upper bound on the logistic map is known when 0 ≤ *r* ≤ 1.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] There are two aspects of the behavior of the logistic map that should be captured by an upper bound in this regime: the asymptotic geometric decay with constant r, and the fast initial decay when *x*0 is close to 1, driven by the (1 − *xn*) term in the recurrence relation.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The special case of *r* = 4 can in fact be solved exactly, as can the case with *r* = 2; however, the general case can only be predicted statistically.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] For rational θ, after a finite number of iterations xn maps into a periodic sequence.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] But almost all θ are irrational, and, for irrational θ, xn never repeats itself – it is non-periodic.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This solution equation clearly demonstrates the two key features of chaos – stretching and folding: the factor 2*n* shows the exponential growth of stretching, which results in sensitive dependence on initial conditions, while the squared sine function keeps xn folded within the range [0,1].
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Just as the squared sine function in the trigonometric solution leads to neither shrinkage nor expansion of the set of points visited, in the latter solution this effect is accomplished by the unit modulus of α.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Since (1 − 2*x*0) ∈ (−1,1) for any value of *x*0 other than the unstable fixed point 0, the term (1 − 2*x*0)2*n* goes to 0 as n goes to infinity, so xn goes to the stable fixed point ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] For the *r* = 4 case, from almost all initial conditions the iterate sequence is chaotic.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Nevertheless, there exist an infinite number of initial conditions that lead to cycles, and indeed there exist cycles of length k for *all* integers *k* > 0.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] We can exploit the relationship of the logistic map to the dyadic transformation (also known as the *bit-shift map*) to find cycles of any length.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] The reason that the dyadic transformation is also called the bit-shift map is that when y is written in binary notation, the map moves the binary point one place to the right (and if the bit to the left of the binary point has become a "1", this "1" is changed to a "0").
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] A cycle of length 3, for example, occurs if an iterate has a 3-bit repeating sequence in its binary expansion (which is not also a one-bit repeating sequence): 001, 010, 100, 110, 101, or 011.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Either of these 3-cycles can be converted to fraction form: for example, the first-given 3-cycle can be written as ⁠1/7⁠ → ⁠2/7⁠ → ⁠4/7⁠ → ⁠1/7⁠.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] We could similarly translate the other bit-shift 3-cycle into its corresponding logistic cycle.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Likewise, cycles of any length k can be found in the bit-shift map and then translated into the corresponding logistic cycles.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] However, since almost all numbers in [0,1) are irrational, almost all initial conditions of the bit-shift map lead to the non-periodicity of chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This is one way to see that the logistic *r* = 4 map is chaotic for almost all initial conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This means that the logistic map with *r* = 4 has 2 fixed points, 1 cycle of length 2, 2 cycles of length 3 and so on.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] This sequence takes a particularly simple form for prime k: 2 ⋅ ⁠2*k* − 1 − 1/*k*⁠.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p03] Since this case of the logistic map is chaotic for almost all initial conditions, all of these finite-length cycles are unstable.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The bifurcation pattern shown above for the logistic map is not limited to the logistic map .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] It appears in a number of maps that satisfy certain conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Here, the domain is 0 ≤ b ≤ 1 and 0 ≤ x ≤ 1 .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The sine map ( 4-1 ) exhibits qualitatively identical behavior to the logistic map ( 1-2 ) : like the logistic map, it also becomes chaotic via a period doubling route as the parameter b increases, and moreover, like the logistic map, it also exhibits a window in the chaotic region .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Both the logistic map and the sine map are one-dimensional maps that map the interval [0, 1] to [0, 1] and satisfy the following property, called unimodal .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The map is differentiable and there exists a unique critical point c in [0, 1] such that $f'(c)=0$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The pattern of stable periodic orbits that emerge from the logistic map is also universal .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In other words, for this type of map, the sequence of stable periodic orbits is the same regardless of the specific form of the map .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] For the logistic map, the parameter interval is 3 < a < 4, but for the sine map ( 4-1 ), the parameter interval for the common sequence of stable periodic orbits is 0.71... < b < 1 .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This universal sequence of stable periodic orbits is called the U sequence .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In addition, the logistic map has the property that its Schwarzian derivative is always negative on the interval [0, 1] .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] where the Schwarzian derivative is negative regardless of the values of a and x.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] It is known that if a one-dimensional mapping from [0, 1] to [0, 1] is unimodal and has a negative Schwarzian derivative, then there is at most one stable periodic orbit.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Let the symbol ∘ denote the composition of maps .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In general, for a topological space X, Y, two maps f : X → X and g : Y → Y are composed by a homeomorphism h : X → Y.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] f and g are said to be phase conjugates if they satisfy the relation .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The concept of phase conjugation plays an important role in the study of dynamical systems .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Phase conjugate f and g exhibit essentially identical behavior, and if the behavior of f is periodic, then g is also periodic, and if the behavior of f is chaotic, then g is also chaotic .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In particular, if a homeomorphism h is linear, then f and g are said to be linearly conjugate .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Every quadratic function is linearly conjugate with every other quadratic function .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] are linearly conjugates of the logistic map for any parameter a .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Equations ( 4-6 ) and ( 4-7 ) are also called logistic maps .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In particular, the form ( 4-7 ) is suitable for time-consuming numerical calculations, since it requires less computational effort .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Moreover, the logistic map $f_{a=4}$ for $r=4$ is topologically conjugate to the following tent map T ( x ) and Bernoulli shift map B ( x ) .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] These phase conjugate relations can be used to prove that the logistic map $f_{a=4}$ is strictly chaotic and to derive the exact solution ( 3-19 ) of $f_{r=4}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] On the set $\Lambda$ introduced in equation ( 3-18 ), the logistic map $f_{r>4}$ is topologically conjugate to the shift map, so we can use this to derive that $f_{r>4}$ on $\Lambda$ is chaotic .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In the logistic map, we have a function $f_{r}(x)=rx(1-x)$ , and we want to study what happens when we iterate the map many times.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The map might fall into a fixed point, a fixed cycle, or chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] When the map falls into a stable fixed cycle of length n , we would find that the graph of $f_{r}^{n}$ and the graph of $x\mapsto x$ intersects at n points, and the slope of the graph of $f_{r}^{n}$ is bounded in $(-1,+1)$ at those intersections.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] For example, when $r=3.0$ , we have a single intersection, with slope bounded in $(-1,+1)$ , indicating that it is a stable single fixed point.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] As r increases to beyond $r=3.0$ , the intersection point splits to two, which is a period doubling.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] For example, when $r=3.4$ , there are three intersection points, with the middle one unstable, and the two others stable.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] As r approaches $r=3.45$ , another period-doubling occurs in the same way.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The period-doublings occur more and more frequently, until at a certain $r\approx 3.56994567$ , the period doublings become infinite, and the map becomes chaotic.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This is the period-doubling route to chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Before the period doubling bifurcation occurs.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] . is exactly 1, and a period doubling bifurcation occurs.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] becomes unstable, splitting into a periodic-2 stable cycle.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] , indicating that it is about to undergo a period-doubling.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] , there are three intersection points, with the middle one unstable, and the two others stable.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] , indicating that it is about to undergo another period-doubling.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Looking at the images, one can notice that at the point of chaos $r^{*}=3.5699\cdots$ , the curve of $f_{r^{*}}^{\infty }$ looks like a fractal.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This suggests to us a scaling limit: if we repeatedly double the function, then scale it up by $\alpha$ for a certain constant $\alpha$ : $f(x)\mapsto -\alpha f(f(-x/\alpha ))$ then at the limit, we would end up with a function g that satisfies $g(x)=-\alpha g(g(-x/\alpha ))$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This is a Feigenbaum function, which appears in most period-doubling routes to chaos (thus it is an instance of **universality**).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Further, as the period-doubling intervals become shorter and shorter, the ratio between two period-doubling intervals converges to a limit, the first Feigenbaum constant $\delta =4.6692016\cdots$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The constant $\alpha$ can be numerically found by trying many possible values.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] For the wrong values, the map does not converge to a limit, but when it is $\alpha =2.5029\dots$ , it converges.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In the chaotic regime, $f_{r}^{\infty }$ , the limit of the iterates of the map, becomes chaotic dark bands interspersed with non-chaotic bright bands.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] When r approaches $r\approx 3.8494344$ , we have another period-doubling approach to chaos, but this time with periods 3, 6, 12, ...
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This again has the same Feigenbaum constants $\delta ,\alpha$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The limit of ${\textstyle f(x)\mapsto -\alpha f(f(-x/\alpha ))}$ is also the same Feigenbaum function.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] We can also consider period-tripling route to chaos by picking a sequence of $r_{1},r_{2},\dots$ such that $r_{n}$ is the lowest value in the period- $3^{n}$ window of the bifurcation diagram.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This has a different pair of Feigenbaum constants $\delta =55.26\dots ,\alpha =9.277\dots$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] And $f_{r}^{\infty }$ converges to the fixed point to $f(x)\mapsto -\alpha f(f(f(-x/\alpha )))$ As another example, period-4-pling has a pair of Feigenbaum constants distinct from that of period-doubling, even though period-4-pling is reached by two period-doublings.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In detail, define $r_{1},r_{2},\dots$ such that $r_{n}$ is the lowest value in the period- $4^{n}$ window of the bifurcation diagram.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This has a different pair of Feigenbaum constants $\delta =981.6\dots ,\alpha =38.82\dots$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In general, each period-multiplying route to chaos has its own pair of Feigenbaum constants.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In fact, there are typically more than one.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] For example, for period-7-pling, there are at least 9 different pairs of Feigenbaum constants.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Generally, ${\textstyle 3\delta \approx 2\alpha ^{2}}$ , and the relation becomes exact as both numbers increase to infinity: $\lim \delta /\alpha ^{2}=2/3$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Universality of one-dimensional maps with parabolic maxima and Feigenbaum constants $\delta =4.669201...$ , $\alpha =2.502907...$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The gradual increase of G at interval $[0,\infty )$ changes dynamics from regular to chaotic one with qualitatively the same bifurcation diagram as those for logistic map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The Feigenbaum constants can be estimated by a renormalization argument.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] By universality, we can use another family of functions that also undergoes repeated period-doubling on its route to chaos, and even though it is not exactly the logistic map, it would still yield the same Feigenbaum constants.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Define the family $f_{r}(x)=-(1+r)x+x^{2}$ The family has an equilibrium point at zero, and as r increases, it undergoes period-doubling bifurcation at $r=r_{0},r_{1},r_{2},...$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The first bifurcation occurs at $r=r_{0}=0$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In order to find out what the stable orbit is like, we "zoom in" around the region of $x=p$ , using the affine transform $T(x)=x/c+p$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] At approximately $S(r)=0$ , the second bifurcation occurs, thus $S(r_{1})\approx 0$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] By self-similarity, the third bifurcation when $S(r)\approx r_{1}$ , and so on.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] These are within 10% of the true values.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The logistic map exhibits numerous characteristics of both periodic and chaotic solutions, whereas the logistic ordinary differential equation (ODE) exhibits regular solutions, commonly referred to as the S-shaped sigmoid function.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The logistic map can be seen as the discrete counterpart of the logistic ODE, and their correlation has been extensively discussed in literature.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] While Lorenz used the logistic map in 1964, it gained widespread popularity from the research of British mathematical biologist Robert May and became widely known as a formula for considering changes in populations of organisms.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In such a logistic map for organism populations, the variable $x_{n}$ represents the number of organisms living in a certain environment (more technically, the population size).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] There are two types of mathematical models for the growth of populations of organisms: discrete-time models using difference equations and continuous-time models using differential equations.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] For example, in the case of a type of insect that dies soon after laying eggs, the population of the insect is counted for each generation, i.e., the number of individuals in the first generation, the number of individuals in the second generation, and so on.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Such examples fit the former discrete-time model.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] On the other hand, when the generations are continuously overlapping, it is compatible with the continuous-time model.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The logistic map corresponds to such a discrete or generation-separated population model.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Let N denote the number of individuals of a single species in an environment.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The simplest model for population growth is one in which the population continues to grow at a constant rate relative to the number of individuals.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Here, N n is the number of individuals in the nth generation, and α is the population growth rate, a positive constant .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] However, in model (5-1), the population continues to grow indefinitely, making it an unrealistic model for most real-world phenomena .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Since there is a limit to the number of individuals that an environment can support, it seems natural that the growth rate α decreases as the population N n increases .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This change in growth rate due to changes in population density is called the density effect .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The following difference equation is the simplest improvement model that reflects the density effect in model (5-1).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Here, a is the maximum growth rate possible in the environment, and b is the strength of the influence of density effects .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Model ( 5-2 ) assumes that the growth rate declines simply in proportion to the number of individuals.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] When using equation (5-2) or equation (5-4) as the population size of an organism, if Nn or xn becomes negative, it becomes meaningless as a population size.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] To prevent this, the condition 0 ≤ x0 ≤ 1 for the initial value x0 and the condition 0 ≤ r ≤ 4 for the parameter a are required.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The logistic map can be derived by considering a difference equation that incorporates density effects in the form $x_{n}=N_{n}/K$ , where the variable $x_{n}$ represents the ratio of the number of individuals $N_{n}$ to the maximum number of individuals K .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The logistic map can also be derived from the discretization of the logistic equation for continuous-time population models.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The name of the logistic map comes from Robert May's introduction of the logistic map from the discretization of the logistic equation.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Here, N is the number or population density of an organism, t is continuous time, and K and r are parameters.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] K is the carrying capacity, and r is the intrinsic rate of natural increase, which is usually positive.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The left-hand side of this equation dN/dt denotes the rate of change of the population size at time t .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The logistic equation ( 5-6 ) appears similar to the logistic map ( 5-4 ), but the behavior of the solutions is quite different from that of the logistic map .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] As long as the initial value N 0 is positive, the population size N of the logistic equation always converges monotonically to K .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] If Δt is small enough, equation ( 5-8 ) serves as a valid approximation to the original equation ( 5-6 ), and coincides with the solution of the original equation as Δt → 0 .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] On the other hand, as Δt becomes large, the solution deviates from the original solution .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Furthermore, due to the relationship in equation ( 5-10 ), increasing Δt is equivalent to increasing the parameter a .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Thus, increasing Δt not only increases the error from the original equation but also produces chaotic behavior in the solution .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] As described above, in biological population dynamics, the logistic map is one of the models of discrete growth processes.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] However, unlike the laws of physics, the logistic map as a model of biological population size is not derived from direct experimental results or universally valid principles .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Although there is some rationality in the way it is derived, it is essentially a "model" thought up in one's mind .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] May, who made the logistic map famous, did not claim that the model he was discussing accurately represented the increase and decrease in population size .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Historically, continuous-time models based on differential equations have been widely used in the study of biological population dynamics, and the application of these continuous-time models has deepened our understanding of biological population dynamics .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] As a discrete-time population model that takes into account density effects, the Ricker model, in which the population size is not negative, is more realistic .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Generally speaking, mathematical models can provide important qualitative information about population dynamics, but their results should not be taken too seriously without experimental support.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Even if the conclusions of mathematical models deviate from those of biological studies, mathematical modeling is still useful because it can provide a useful control.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Biological issues may be raised by reviewing the model construction process and settings, or the biological knowledge and assumptions that the model is based on.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Although the logistic map is too simple to be realistic as a population model, its results suggest that a variety of population fluctuations may occur due to the dynamics inherent in the population itself, regardless of random influences from the environment.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The degree of freedom or dimension of a one-variable logistic map as a system is one .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] On the other hand, in the real natural world, it is thought that there are many chaotic systems with many degrees of freedom, not only in time but also in space .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Alternatively, the synchronization phenomenon of oscillators performing chaotic motion is also a research subject .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] To investigate such things, there is a method of coupled maps that couples many difference equations (maps) .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The logistic map is often used as a subject of coupled map model research .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The reason for this is that the logistic map itself has already been well investigated as a typical model of chaos, and there is an accumulation of research on it .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] There are various methods for the specific coupling in the coupled map model .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Suppose a total of N maps are coupled, and the state of the i-th map at time n is represented by $x_{n}(i)$ .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In these equations, f( x ) is the specific map to incorporate into the coupled map model, and applies here if the logistic map is used .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In equations ( 6-1 ) and ( 6-2 ), ε and D are parameters called coupling coefficients, which indicate the strength of the coupling between the maps .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] On the other hand, when the logistic map is incorporated into a coupled map model, the parameter a of the logistic map indicates the strength of the nonlinearity of the model .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] By changing the value of a and the value of ε or D, various phenomena appear in the coupled map system of logistic maps.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] For example, in model ( 6-2 ), when D is increased to a value Dc or more, x and y oscillate chaotically while synchronously .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Even below Dc, not only do chaotic oscillations occur in a continuous manner .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] When D is in a certain range, x and y oscillate with two periods even though r = 4 .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] When a = 3.8, behavior in which synchronous and asynchronous states alternate continuously is also observed .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In a study of the application of the logistic map to a globally coupled map with a large degree of freedom ( 6-1 ), a phenomenon called chaotic itinerancy was found .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In the fields of computer simulation and information security, the creation of pseudorandom numbers using a computer is an important technique, and one of the methods for generating pseudorandom numbers is the use of chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Although a pseudorandom number generator based on chaos with sufficient performance has not yet been realized, several methods have been proposed.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Several researchers have also investigated the possibility of creating a pseudorandom number generator based on chaos for the logistic map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Parameter r = 4 is often used for pseudorandom number generation using the logistic map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Historically, as described below, in 1947, shortly after the birth of electronic computers, Stanisław Ulam and John von Neumann also pointed out the possibility of a pseudorandom number generator using the logistic map with r = 4.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] However, the distribution of points for the logistic map $f_{r=4}$ is as shown in equation ( 3-17 ), and the numbers that are generated are biased toward 0 and 1.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Therefore, some processing is required to obtain unbiased uniform random numbers.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] A method for converting the obtained values to a uniform distribution using the tent map ( 4-8 ).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The resulting number is converted to either 0 or 1 using a threshold, as in the coin tossing analogy above, and this process is repeated to obtain a uniformly random bit string.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In addition, the sequences $x_{n}$ and $x_{n}+1$ obtained by the logistic map are strongly correlated, which makes it problematic for pseudorandom sequences.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] One way to solve this is to generate the sequence $x_{0},x_{1},x_{2},...$ for each iteration of the map, rather than generating the sequence $x_{0},x_{\tau },x_{2\tau },...$ for some number of iterations τ > 1.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] For example, it is said that good pseudorandom numbers can be obtained for method 1 with τ > 10 or τ > 13, and for method 2 with τ > 16.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] A common problem with digitally calculating chaos using a computer is that, because a computer has a finite calculation precision, it is in principle impossible to obtain a truly aperiodic sequence, which is the nature of chaos, and instead outputs a finite periodic sequence.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Even if aperiodic sequences cannot be obtained in principle, sequences with as long a period as possible are desirable for generating pseudorandom numbers.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In addition, with the logistic map, $f_{r=4}$ there is a risk that the value will fall to the fixed point 0 during the calculation and remain constant.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] On the other hand, the logistic map always takes values in the open interval (0, 1), so it can be calculated without problems not only with floating point but also with fixed point, and can enjoy the advantages of fixed point arithmetic.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] It has been pointed out that fixed point has a longer period than floating point for the same number of bits, and that unintended convergence to 0 can be eliminated.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Dynamical systems defined by complex analytic functions are also of interest.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] where the parameter c and the variable z are complex numbers.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This map is essentially the same as the logistic map (1–2).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] As mentioned above, the map (6–3) is topologically conjugate to the logistic map (1–2) through a linear function.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] When the iteration of the map (6–3) is calculated with a fixed parameter c and varying the initial value $z_{0}$ , a set of $z_{0}$ such that $z_{n}$ does not diverge to infinity as n → ∞ is called a filled Julia set.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Furthermore, the boundary of a filled Julia set is called a Julia set.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] When the iteration of the map (6–3) is calculated with a fixed initial value $z_{0}=0$ and varying the parameter c, a set of c such that z does not diverge to infinity is called a Mandelbrot set.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The Julia sets and Mandelbrot sets of the map (6–3) generate fractal figures that are described as "mystical looking" and "extremely mysterious".
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In particular, in the Mandelbrot set, each disk in the diagram corresponds to a region of asymptotically stable periodic orbits of a certain period.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] By juxtaposing the logistic map orbit diagram with the Mandelbrot set diagram, it is possible to see that the asymptotically stable fixed points, period doubling bifurcations, and period-three windows of the logistic map orbit diagram correspond on the real axis to the Mandelbrot set diagram.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] If we interpret the logistic map as a model of the population of each generation of organisms, it is possible that the population of the next generation will affect not only the population of the current generation, but also the population of the generation before that.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] where the number of individuals in the previous generation, $x_{n-1}$ , is included in the equation as a negative density effect .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] If $x_{n+1}=y_{n}$ , then equation ( 6-4 ) can be replaced by the following two-variable difference equation .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This dynamical system is used to study bifurcation of quasi-periodic attractors and is called the delayed logistic map .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] The delayed logistic map exhibits a Neimark–Sacker bifurcation at r = 2, where the asymptotically stable fixed point becomes unstable and an asymptotically stable invariant curve forms around the unstable fixed point .
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Before the iteration of maps became relevant to dynamical systems, mathematicians Gaston Julia and Pierre Fatou studied the iteration of complex functions.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Julia and Fatou's work was broad, focusing on analytic functions.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In particular, they studied the behavior of the following complex quadratic function, also shown in equation (6–3), in the 1920s.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Julia and Fatu also recognized chaotic behavior in Julia sets, but because there was no computer graphics at the time, no one followed suit and their research stalled.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Research on complex dynamical systems then declined until the late 1970s, and it was not until the appearance of Benoit Mandelbrot and others that the rich dynamical behavior exhibited by maps on the complex plane was noticed.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] They pointed out that pseudorandom numbers can be generated by the repeated composition of quadratic functions such as.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In modern terms, this equation corresponds to the logistic map with r = 4.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] At that time, the word "chaos" had not yet been used, but Ulam and von Neumann were already paying attention to the generation of complex sequences using nonlinear functions.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In their report, Ulam and von Neumann also clarified that the map (7–2) and the tent map are topologically conjugate, and that the invariant measure of the sequence of this map is given by equation (3–17).
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] There have since been some detailed investigations of quadratic maps of the form with arbitrary parameter a.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This line of research is essential for dynamical systems, and Mühlberg has also investigated the period-doubling branching cascades of this map, showing the existence of an accumulation point λ = 1.401155189....
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Others, such as the work of the Soviet Oleksandr Sharkovsky in 1964, the French Igor Gumowski and Christian Mila in 1969, and Nicholas Metropolis in 1973, have revealed anomalous behavior of simple one-variable difference equations such as the logistic map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Later, in the early 1970s, mathematical biologist Robert May encountered the model of equation (1–2) while working on an ecological problem.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] May introduced equation (1–2), i.e., the logistic map, by discretizing the logistic equation in time.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] He mathematically analyzed the behavior of the logistic map, and published his results in 1973 and 1974.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Numerical experiments were performed on the logistic map to investigate the change in its behavior depending on the parameter r.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In 1976, he published a paper in *Nature* entitled "Simple mathematical models with very complicated dynamics".
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This paper was a review paper that focused on the logistic map and emphasized and drew attention to the fact that even simple nonlinear functions can produce extremely complex behaviors such as period-doubling bifurcation cascades and chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] This paper in particular caused a great stir and was accepted by the scientific community due to May's status as a mathematical biologist, the clarity of his research results, and above all, the shocking content that a simple parabolic equation can produce surprisingly complex behavior.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Through May's research, the logistic map attracted many researchers to chaos research and became such a famous mathematical model that it is said to have restarted the flow of chaos research.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] May also drew attention to the paper by using the term "chaos", which was used by Tien-Yen Li and James York in their paper "Period three implies chaos".
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Although some disagree, Li and York's paper is considered the first to use the word "chaos" as a mathematical term, and is credited with coining the term "chaos" to refer to deterministic, chaotic behavior.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Li and York completed the paper in 1973, but when they submitted it to *The American Mathematical Monthly*, they were told that it was too technical and that it should be significantly rewritten to make it easier to understand, and it was rejected.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] However, the following year, in 1974, May came to give a special guest lecture at the University of Maryland where Lee and York were working, and talked about the logistic map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] At the time, May did not yet understand what was happening in the chaotic domain of the logistic map, but Lee and York were also unaware of the period-doubling cascade of the logistic map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Excited by May's talk, Lee and York caught up with May after the lecture and told him about their results, which surprised May.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Lee and York quickly rewrote the rejected paper, and the resubmitted paper was published in 1975.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] May and George Oster had also noticed the scaling law, but they were unable to follow it in depth.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] Feigenbaum discovered that the same constant also appeared in the sine map shown in equation (4–1), and realized that this scaling law had a universality that went beyond the logistic map.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] In 1980, a rigorous proof of this result was given by Pierre Collé, Jean-Pierre Eckman, Oscar Rumford, and others.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] At about the same time as Feigenbaum, or later, physicists discovered the same period doubling cascade and the Feigenbaum constant in real life, and chaos, which had previously been seen as a strictly mathematical phenomenon, had a major impact on the field of physics as well.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] However, there is criticism of the tendency to downplay research results from before the popularity of chaos, and to attribute many of those results to rediscoverers who used the logistic map, etc.
[src:chaos-theory/logistic-map-p04] May himself respects the existence of previous research, but positions his own achievement as not being "the first to independently discover the strange mathematical behavior of quadratic maps", but as being one of the "last researchers to emphasize their broad implications in science".
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The **Lorenz system** is a set of three ordinary differential equations, first developed by the meteorologist Edward Lorenz while studying atmospheric convection.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] It is a classic example of a system that can exhibit chaotic behavior, meaning its output can be highly sensitive to small changes in its starting conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] For certain values of its parameters, the system's solutions form a complex, looping pattern known as the **Lorenz attractor**.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The shape of this attractor, when graphed, is famously said to resemble a butterfly.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The system's extreme sensitivity to initial conditions gave rise to the popular concept of the butterfly effect—the idea that a small event, like the flap of a butterfly's wings, could ultimately alter large-scale weather patterns.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] While the system is deterministic—its future behavior is fully determined by its initial conditions—its chaotic nature makes long-term prediction practically impossible.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The behavior of the system depends on the choice of parameters.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] For some ranges of parameters, the system is predictable: trajectories settle into fixed points or simple periodic orbits, making the long-term behavior easy to describe.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] For example, when *ρ* < 1, all solutions converge to the origin, and for certain moderate values of ρ, σ, and β, solutions converge to symmetric steady states.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] In contrast, for other parameter ranges, the system becomes chaotic.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] With the well-known parameters *σ* = 10, *ρ* = 28, and *β* = ⁠8/3⁠, the solutions never settle down but instead trace out the butterfly-shaped Lorenz attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] In this regime, small differences in initial conditions grow exponentially.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] In 1963, Edward Lorenz developed the system as a simplified mathematical model for atmospheric convection.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] He was attempting to model the way air moves when heated from below and cooled from above.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The model was developed with the assistance of Ellen Fetter, who performed the numerical simulations and created the figures, and Margaret Hamilton, who aided in the initial computations.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The constants σ, ρ, and β are parameters representing physical properties of the system: σ is the Prandtl number, ρ is the Rayleigh number, and β relates to the physical dimensions of the fluid layer itself.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] From a technical standpoint, the Lorenz system is nonlinear, aperiodic, three-dimensional, and deterministic.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] While originally for weather, the equations have since been found to model behavior in a wide variety of systems, including lasers, dynamos, electric circuits, and even some chemical reactions.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The Lorenz equations have been the subject of hundreds of research articles and at least one book-length study.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] One normally assumes that the parameters σ, ρ, and β are positive.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The system exhibits chaotic behavior for these (and nearby) values.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] If *ρ* < 1 then there is only one equilibrium point, which is at the origin.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] This point corresponds to no convection.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] All orbits converge to the origin, which is a global attractor, when *ρ* < 1.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] which can hold only for positive ρ if *σ* > *β* + 1.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] At the critical value, both equilibrium points lose stability through a subcritical Hopf bifurcation.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] When *ρ* = 28, *σ* = 10, and *β* = ⁠8/3⁠, the Lorenz system has chaotic solutions (but not all solutions are chaotic).
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] Almost all initial points will tend to an invariant set – the Lorenz attractor – a strange attractor, a fractal, and a self-excited attractor with respect to all three equilibria.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] Its Hausdorff dimension is estimated from above by the Lyapunov dimension (Kaplan-Yorke dimension) as 2.06±0.01, and the correlation dimension is estimated to be 2.05±0.01.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The Lorenz attractor is difficult to analyze, but the action of the differential equation on the attractor is described by a fairly simple geometric model.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] Proving that this is indeed the case is the fourteenth problem on the list of Smale's problems.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] This problem was the first one to be resolved, by Warwick Tucker in 2002.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] For other values of ρ, the system displays knotted periodic orbits.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] For example, with *ρ* = 99.96 it becomes a *T*(3,2) torus knot.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] In Figure 4 of his paper, Lorenz plotted the relative maximum value in the z direction achieved by the system against the previous relative maximum in the z direction.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] This procedure later became known as a Lorenz map (not to be confused with a Poincaré plot, which plots the intersections of a trajectory with a prescribed surface).
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The resulting plot has a shape very similar to the tent map.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] Lorenz also found that when the maximum z value is above a certain cut-off, the system will switch to the next lobe.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] Combining this with the chaos known to be exhibited by the tent map, he showed that the system switches between the two lobes chaotically.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] As shown in Lorenz's original paper, the Lorenz system is a reduced version of a larger system studied earlier by Barry Saltzman.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The Lorenz equations are derived from the Oberbeck–Boussinesq approximation to the equations describing fluid circulation in a shallow layer of fluid, heated uniformly from below and cooled uniformly from above.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] This fluid circulation is known as Rayleigh–Bénard convection.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The fluid is assumed to circulate in two dimensions (vertical and horizontal) with periodic rectangular boundary conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] This reduces the model equations to a set of three coupled, nonlinear ordinary differential equations.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] A detailed derivation may be found, for example, in nonlinear dynamics texts from Hilborn (2000), Appendix C; Bergé, Pomeau & Vidal (1984), Appendix D; or Shen (2016), Supplementary Materials.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The revised view, which is a build-up of the conventional view, is used to suggest that “the chaotic and regular features found in theoretical Lorenz models could better represent features of the Earth's atmosphere”.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] Smale's 14th problem asks, "Do the properties of the Lorenz attractor exhibit that of a strange attractor?".
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The problem was answered affirmatively by Warwick Tucker in 2002.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] To prove this result, Tucker used rigorous numerics methods like interval arithmetic and normal forms.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] First, Tucker defined a cross section $\Sigma \subset \{x_{3}=r-1\}$ that is cut transversely by the flow trajectories.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] From this, one can define the first-return map P , which assigns to each $x\in \Sigma$ the point $P(x)$ where the trajectory of x first intersects $\Sigma$ .
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] Then the proof is split in three main points that are proved and imply the existence of a strange attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] To prove the first point, we notice that the cross section $\Sigma$ is cut by two arcs formed by $P(\Sigma )$ .
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] Tucker covers the location of these two arcs by small rectangles $R_{i}$ , the union of these rectangles gives N .
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] Now, the goal is to prove that for all points in N , the flow will bring back the points in $\Sigma$ , in N .
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] To do that, we take a plan $\Sigma '$ below $\Sigma$ at a distance h small, then by taking the center $c_{i}$ of $R_{i}$ and using Euler integration method, one can estimate where the flow will bring $c_{i}$ in $\Sigma '$ which gives us a new point $c_{i}'$ .
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] Then, one can estimate where the points in $\Sigma$ will be mapped in $\Sigma '$ using Taylor expansion, this gives us a new rectangle $R_{i}'$ centered on $c_{i}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] Thus we know that all points in $R_{i}$ will be mapped in $R_{i}'$ .
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The goal is to do this method recursively until the flow comes back to $\Sigma$ and we obtain a rectangle $Rf_{i}$ in $\Sigma$ such that we know that $P(R_{i})\subset Rf_{i}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] The problem is that our estimation may become imprecise after several iterations, thus what Tucker does is to split $R_{i}'$ into smaller rectangles $R_{i,j}$ and then apply the process recursively.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] Another problem is that as we are applying this algorithm, the flow becomes more 'horizontal', leading to a dramatic increase in imprecision.
[src:chaos-theory/lorenz-system] To prevent this, the algorithm changes the orientation of the cross sections, becoming either horizontal or vertical.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] In mathematics, the **Lyapunov exponent** or **Lyapunov characteristic exponent** of a dynamical system is a quantity that characterizes the exponential rate of separation of infinitesimally close trajectories.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] where $\lambda$ is the Lyapunov exponent.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The rate of separation can be different for different orientations of initial separation vector.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Thus, there is a **spectrum of Lyapunov exponents**—equal in number to the dimensionality of the phase space.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] It is common to refer to the largest one as the **maximal Lyapunov exponent** (MLE), because it determines a notion of predictability for a dynamical system.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] A positive MLE is usually taken as an indication that the system is chaotic (provided some other conditions are met, e.g., phase space compactness).
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] This is because for the MLE to be more than 0, the average derivative needs to be more than 1, since we find its logarithms.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] If the average derivatives are above 1, it means that the function grows exponentially, which makes it so that any small change between initial values increase from their original value, so the function is divergent.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] If it is less than 0, it means that the average derivative is less than 1, which means that the function is decreasing, which would make any changes in the initial values decrease over time, making the function convergent.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Note that an arbitrary initial separation vector will typically contain some component in the direction associated with the MLE, and because of the exponential growth rate, the effect of the other exponents will diminish over time.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The exponent is named after Aleksandr Lyapunov.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The limit $|{\boldsymbol {\delta }}_{0}|\to 0$ ensures the validity of the linear approximation at any time.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] For a dynamical system with evolution equation ${\dot {x}}_{i}=f_{i}(x)$ in an *n*–dimensional phase space, the spectrum of Lyapunov exponents $\{\lambda _{1},\lambda _{2},\ldots ,\lambda _{n}\}\,,$ in general, depends on the starting point $x_{0}$ .
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] However, we will usually be interested in the attractor (or attractors) of a dynamical system, and there will normally be one set of exponents associated with each attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The choice of starting point may determine which attractor the system ends up on, if there is more than one.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The matrix Y describes how a small change at the point $x(0)$ propagates to the final point $x(t)$ .
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The limit $\Lambda =\lim _{t\rightarrow \infty }{\frac {1}{2t}}\log(Y(t)Y^{T}(t))$ defines a matrix $\Lambda$ (the conditions for the existence of the limit are given by the Oseledets theorem).
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The Lyapunov exponents $\lambda _{i}$ are defined by the eigenvalues of $\Lambda$ .
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The set of Lyapunov exponents will be the same for almost all starting points of an ergodic component of the dynamical system.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The singular values $\{\alpha _{j}{\big (}X(t){\big )}\}_{1}^{n}$ of the matrix $X(t)$ are the square roots of the eigenvalues of the matrix $X(t)^{*}X(t)$ .
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Perron that the requirement of regularity of the first approximation is substantial.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Perron constructed an example of a second-order system, where the first approximation has negative Lyapunov exponents along a zero solution of the original system but, at the same time, this zero solution of the original nonlinear system is Lyapunov unstable.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Furthermore, in a certain neighborhood of this zero solution almost all solutions of the original system have positive Lyapunov exponents.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Also, it is possible to construct a reverse example in which the first approximation has positive Lyapunov exponents along a zero solution of the original system but, at the same time, this zero solution of original nonlinear system is Lyapunov stable.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The effect of sign inversion of Lyapunov exponents of solutions of the original system and the system of first approximation with the same initial data was subsequently called the Perron effect.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Perron's counterexample shows that a negative largest Lyapunov exponent does not, in general, indicate stability, and that a positive largest Lyapunov exponent does not, in general, indicate chaos.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Therefore, time-varying linearization requires additional justification.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] If the system is conservative (i.e., there is no dissipation), a volume element of the phase space will stay the same along a trajectory.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Thus the sum of all Lyapunov exponents must be zero.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] If the system is dissipative, the sum of Lyapunov exponents is negative.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] If the system is a flow and the trajectory does not converge to a single point, one exponent is always zero—the Lyapunov exponent corresponding to the eigenvalue of L with an eigenvector in the direction of the flow.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The Lyapunov spectrum can be used to give an estimate of the rate of entropy production, of the fractal dimension, and of the Hausdorff dimension of the considered dynamical system.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Moreover, the sum of all the positive Lyapunov exponents gives an estimate of the Kolmogorov–Sinai entropy accordingly to Pesin's theorem.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Along with widely used numerical methods for estimating and computing the Lyapunov dimension there is an effective analytical approach, which is based on the direct Lyapunov method with special Lyapunov-like functions.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The Lyapunov exponents of bounded trajectory and the Lyapunov dimension of attractor are invariant under diffeomorphism of the phase space.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The multiplicative inverse of the largest Lyapunov exponent is sometimes referred in literature as Lyapunov time, and defines the characteristic *e*-folding time.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] For chaotic orbits, the Lyapunov time will be finite, whereas for regular orbits it will be infinite.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Generally the calculation of Lyapunov exponents, as defined above, cannot be carried out analytically, and in most cases one must resort to numerical techniques.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] An early example, which also constituted the first demonstration of the exponential divergence of chaotic trajectories, was carried out by R.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Currently, the most commonly used numerical procedure estimates the L matrix based on averaging several finite time approximations of the limit defining L .
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] One of the most used and effective numerical techniques to calculate the Lyapunov spectrum for a smooth dynamical system relies on periodic Gram–Schmidt orthonormalization of the Lyapunov vectors to avoid a misalignment of all the vectors along the direction of maximal expansion.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The Lyapunov spectrum of various models are described.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Source code is provided for several nonlinear systems, including the Hénon map, the Lorenz system, and a delay differential equation.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Calculating Lyapunov exponents from limited experimental data presents significant challenges.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The primary difficulty arises because such data is typically confined to the system's attractor and does not explore the full phase space.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] This confinement results in a 'singular' dataset with minimal extension along certain directions.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] These singular directions are precisely those associated with the more negative Lyapunov exponents, making them notoriously difficult to determine accurately.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] To address this, one effective technique is to use nonlinear mappings to model the evolution of small displacements from the attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] This approach can dramatically improve the ability to recover the full Lyapunov spectrum, but it is highly sensitive to noise and requires very clean data to be effective.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Whereas the (global) Lyapunov exponent gives a measure for the total predictability of a system, it is sometimes of interest to estimate the local predictability around a point *x*0 in phase space.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] This may be done through the eigenvalues of the Jacobian matrix *J*0(*x*0).
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] These eigenvalues are also called local Lyapunov exponents.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Local exponents are not invariant under a nonlinear change of coordinates.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] This term is normally used regarding synchronization of chaos, in which there are two systems that are coupled, usually in a unidirectional manner so that there is a drive (or master) system and a response (or slave) system.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] The conditional exponents are those of the response system with the drive system treated as simply the source of a (chaotic) drive signal.
[src:chaos-theory/lyapunov-exponent] Synchronization occurs when all of the conditional exponents are negative.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] In the mathematical field of dynamical systems, an **attractor** is a set of states toward which a system tends to evolve, for a wide variety of starting conditions of the system.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] System values that get close enough to the attractor values remain close even if slightly disturbed.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] In finite-dimensional systems, the evolving variable may be represented algebraically as an *n*-dimensional vector.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The attractor is a region in *n*-dimensional space.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] In physical systems, the *n* dimensions may be, for example, two or three positional coordinates for each of one or more physical entities; in economic systems, they may be separate variables such as the inflation rate and the unemployment rate.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] If the evolving variable is two- or three-dimensional, the attractor of the dynamic process can be represented geometrically in two or three dimensions, (as for example in the three-dimensional case depicted to the right).
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] An attractor can be a point, a finite set of points, a curve, a manifold, or even a complicated set with a fractal structure known as a *strange attractor* (see strange attractor below).
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] If the variable is a scalar, the attractor is a subset of the real number line.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Describing the attractors of chaotic dynamical systems has been one of the achievements of chaos theory.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] A trajectory of the dynamical system in the attractor does not have to satisfy any special constraints except for remaining on the attractor, forward in time.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The trajectory may be periodic or chaotic.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] If a set of points is periodic or chaotic, but the flow in the neighborhood is away from the set, the set is not an attractor, but instead is called a *repeller* (or *repellor*).
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] A dynamical system is generally described by one or more differential or difference equations.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The equations of a given dynamical system specify its behavior over any given short period of time.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] To determine the system's behavior for a longer period, it is often necessary to integrate the equations, either through analytical means or through iteration, often with the aid of computers.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Dynamical systems in the physical world tend to arise from dissipative systems: if it were not for some driving force, the motion would cease.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] (Dissipation may come from internal friction, thermodynamic losses, or loss of material, among many causes.) The dissipation and the driving force tend to balance, killing off initial transients and settle the system into its typical behavior.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The subset of the phase space of the dynamical system corresponding to the typical behavior is the attractor, also known as the attracting section or attractee.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Invariant sets and limit sets are similar to the attractor concept.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] An *invariant set* is a set that evolves to itself under the dynamics.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] A *limit set* is a set of points such that there exists some initial state that ends up arbitrarily close to the limit set (i.e. to each point of the set) as time goes to infinity.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Attractors are limit sets, but not all limit sets are attractors: It is possible to have some points of a system converge to a limit set, but different points when perturbed slightly off the limit set may get knocked off and never return to the vicinity of the limit set.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] For example, the damped pendulum has two invariant points: the point *x*0 of minimum height and the point *x*1 of maximum height.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The point x0 is also a limit set, as trajectories converge to it; the point *x*1 is not a limit set.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Because of the dissipation due to air resistance, the point x0 is also an attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] If there was no dissipation, *x*0 would not be an attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Aristotle believed that objects moved only as long as they were pushed, which is an early formulation of a dissipative attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Some attractors are known to be chaotic (see strange attractor), in which case the evolution of any two distinct points of the attractor result in exponentially diverging trajectories, which complicates prediction when even the smallest noise is present in the system.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Let t represent time and let $f(t,\cdot )$ be a function which specifies the dynamics of the system.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] That is, if a is a point in an n -dimensional phase space, representing the initial state of the system, then $f(0,a)=a$ and, for a positive value of t , $f(t,a)$ is the result of the evolution of this state after t units of time.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Since the basin of attraction contains an open set containing A , every point that is sufficiently close to A is attracted to A .
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The definition of an attractor uses a metric on the phase space, but the resulting notion usually depends only on the topology of the phase space.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] In the case of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , the Euclidean norm is typically used.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Many other definitions of attractor occur in the literature.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] For example, some authors require that an attractor have positive measure (preventing a point from being an attractor), others relax the requirement that $B(A)$ be a neighborhood.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Attractors are portions or subsets of the phase space of a dynamical system.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Until the 1960s, attractors were thought of as being simple geometric subsets of the phase space, like points, lines, surfaces, and simple regions of three-dimensional space.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] More complex attractors that cannot be categorized as simple geometric subsets, such as topologically wild sets, were known of at the time but were thought to be fragile anomalies.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Stephen Smale was able to show that his horseshoe map was robust and that its attractor had the structure of a Cantor set.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Two simple attractors are a fixed point and the limit cycle.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Attractors can take on many other geometric shapes (phase space subsets).
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] But when these sets (or the motions within them) cannot be easily described as simple combinations (e.g. intersection and union) of fundamental geometric objects (e.g. lines, surfaces, spheres, toroids, manifolds), then the attractor is called a *strange attractor*.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] A fixed point of a function or transformation is a point that is mapped to itself by the function or transformation.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] If we regard the evolution of a dynamical system as a series of transformations, then there may or may not be a point which remains fixed under each transformation.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] But the fixed point(s) of a dynamic system is not necessarily an attractor of the system.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] For example, if the bowl containing a rolling marble was inverted and the marble was balanced on top of the bowl, the center bottom (now top) of the bowl is a fixed state, but not an attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] This is equivalent to the difference between stable and unstable equilibria.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] In the case of a marble on top of an inverted bowl (a hill), that point at the top of the bowl (hill) is a fixed point (equilibrium), but not an attractor (unstable equilibrium).
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] In the case of a marble on top of an inverted bowl, even if the bowl seems perfectly hemispherical, and the marble's spherical shape, are both much more complex surfaces when examined under a microscope, and their shapes change or deform during contact.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Any physical surface can be seen to have a rough terrain of multiple peaks, valleys, saddle points, ridges, ravines, and plains.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] There are many points in this surface terrain (and the dynamic system of a similarly rough marble rolling around on this microscopic terrain) that are considered stationary or fixed points, some of which are categorized as attractors.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] In a discrete-time system, an attractor can take the form of a finite number of points that are visited in sequence.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Each of these points is called a periodic point.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] This is illustrated by the logistic map, which depending on its specific parameter value can have an attractor consisting of 1 point, 2 points, 2*n* points, 3 points, 3×2*n* points, 4 points, 5 points, or any given positive integer number of points.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] A limit cycle is a periodic orbit of a continuous dynamical system that is isolated.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Examples include the swings of a pendulum clock, and the heartbeat while resting.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] For a physical pendulum under friction, the resting state will be a fixed-point attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The difference with the clock pendulum is that there, energy is injected by the escapement mechanism to maintain the cycle.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] There may be more than one frequency in the periodic trajectory of the system through the state of a limit cycle.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] For example, in physics, one frequency may dictate the rate at which a planet orbits a star while a second frequency describes the oscillations in the distance between the two bodies.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] If two of these frequencies form an irrational fraction (i.e. they are incommensurate), the trajectory is no longer closed, and the limit cycle becomes a limit torus.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] This kind of attractor is called an *N**t* -torus if there are Nt incommensurate frequencies.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] A time series corresponding to this attractor is a quasiperiodic series: A discretely sampled sum of Nt periodic functions (not necessarily sine waves) with incommensurate frequencies.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Such a time series does not have a strict periodicity, but its power spectrum still consists only of sharp lines.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] An attractor is called *strange* if it has a fractal structure; that is, if it has non-integer Hausdorff dimension.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] This is often the case when the dynamics on it are chaotic, but strange nonchaotic attractors also exist.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Thus a dynamic system with a chaotic attractor is locally unstable yet globally stable: once some sequences have entered the attractor, nearby points diverge from one another but never depart from the attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The term *strange attractor* was coined by David Ruelle and Floris Takens to describe the attractor resulting from a series of bifurcations of a system describing fluid flow.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Strange attractors are often differentiable in a few directions, but some are like a Cantor dust, and therefore not differentiable.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Strange attractors may also be found in the presence of noise, where they may be shown to support invariant random probability measures of Sinai–Ruelle–Bowen type.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Examples of strange attractors include the double-scroll attractor, Hénon attractor, Rössler attractor, and Lorenz attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The behavior of a dynamical system may be influenced by its parameters or the choice of initial conditions.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The logistic map, defined as $x_{n+1}=rx_{n}(1-x_{n})$ , is a well-studied example of a system dependent on one parameter r .
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Its attractors for various values of r are shown in the figure.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] For small r the attractor is a single fixed point, which is shown on the bifurcation diagram as one line.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] For other choices of r , more than one value of x may become attracting: at $r\approx 3$ the fixed point splits in two creating a period 2 cycle during a period-doubling bifurcation.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] As r increases, chaos emerges through a period-doubling cascade, meaning the attractor consists of an infinte number of points.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] At $r\approx 3.83$ a period 3 orbit can be found.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] It follows from the Sharkovskii's theorem that orbits of any natural period are present in the system.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Thus one dynamic equation can have vastly different attractors depending on the choice of parameters.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] An attractor's basin of attraction is the region of the phase space, over which iterations are defined, such that any point (any initial condition) in that region will asymptotically be iterated into the attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] For a stable linear system, every point in the phase space is in the basin of attraction.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] However, in nonlinear systems, some points may map directly or asymptotically to infinity, while other points may lie in a different basin of attraction and map asymptotically into a different attractor; other initial conditions may be in or map directly into a non-attracting point or cycle.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] A univariate linear homogeneous difference equation $x_{t}=ax_{t-1}$ diverges to infinity if $|a|>1$ from all initial points except 0; there is no attractor and therefore no basin of attraction.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] But if $|a|<1$ all points on the number line map asymptotically (or directly in the case of 0) to 0; 0 is the attractor, and the entire number line is the basin of attraction.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] But if the largest eigenvalue is less than 1 in magnitude, all initial vectors will asymptotically converge to the zero vector, which is the attractor; the entire n -dimensional space of potential initial vectors is the basin of attraction.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Similar features apply to linear differential equations.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The scalar equation $dx/dt=ax$ causes all initial values of x except zero to diverge to infinity if $a>0$ but to converge to an attractor at the value 0 if $a<0$ , making the entire number line the basin of attraction for 0.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] And the matrix system $dX/dt=AX$ gives divergence from all initial points except the vector of zeroes if any eigenvalue of the matrix A is positive; but if all the eigenvalues are negative the vector of zeroes is an attractor whose basin of attraction is the entire phase space.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Equations or systems that are nonlinear can give rise to a richer variety of behavior than can linear systems.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] One example is Newton's method of iterating to a root of a nonlinear expression.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] If the expression has more than one real root, some starting points for the iterative algorithm will lead to one of the roots asymptotically, and other starting points will lead to another.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The basins of attraction for the expression's roots are generally not simple—it is not simply that the points nearest one root all map there, giving a basin of attraction consisting of nearby points.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The basins of attraction can be infinite in number and arbitrarily small.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Newton's method can also be applied to complex functions to find their roots.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Each root has a basin of attraction in the complex plane; these basins can be mapped as in the image shown.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] As can be seen, the combined basin of attraction for a particular root can have many disconnected regions.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] For many complex functions, the boundaries of the basins of attraction are fractals.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] Parabolic partial differential equations may have finite-dimensional attractors.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The diffusive part of the equation damps higher frequencies and in some cases leads to a global attractor.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] The *Ginzburg–Landau*, the *Kuramoto–Sivashinsky*, and the two-dimensional, forced Navier–Stokes equations are all known to have global attractors of finite dimension.
[src:chaos-theory/strange-attractor] For the three-dimensional, incompressible Navier–Stokes equation with periodic boundary conditions, if it has a global attractor, then this attractor will be of finite dimensions.
